# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: coating
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] In the 1980s, 3D printing techniques were considered suitable only for the production of functional or aesthetic prototypes, and a more appropriate term for it at the time was rapid prototyping.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] As of 2019, the precision, repeatability, and material range of 3D printing have increased to the point that some 3D printing processes are considered viable as an industrial-production technology; in this context, the term *additive manufacturing* can be used synonymously with *3D printing*.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] One of the key advantages of 3D printing is the ability to produce very complex shapes or geometries that would be otherwise infeasible to construct by hand, including hollow parts or parts with internal truss structures to reduce weight while creating less material waste.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] Fused deposition modeling (FDM), which uses a continuous filament of a thermoplastic material, is the most common 3D printing process in use as of 2020.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] The umbrella term *additive manufacturing (AM)* gained popularity in the 2000s, inspired by the theme of material being added together (in any of various ways).
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] In contrast, the term *subtractive manufacturing* appeared as a retronym for the large family of machining processes with material *removal* as their common process.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] The term *3D printing* still referred only to the polymer technologies in most minds, and the term *AM* was more likely to be used in metalworking and end-use part production contexts than among polymer, inkjet, or stereolithography enthusiasts.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] Until recently, the term *3D printing* has been associated with machines low in price or capability.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] *3D printing* and *additive manufacturing* reflect that the technologies share the theme of material addition or joining throughout a 3D work envelope under automated control.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] Other terms that have been used as synonyms or hypernyms have included *desktop manufacturing*, *rapid manufacturing* (as the logical production-level successor to *rapid prototyping*), and *on-demand manufacturing* (which echoes *on-demand printing* in the 2D sense of *printing*).
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] Today, the term *subtractive* has not replaced the term *machining*, instead complementing it when a term that covers any removal method is needed.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] Agile tooling is the use of modular means to design tooling that is produced by additive manufacturing or 3D printing methods to enable quick prototyping and responses to tooling and fixture needs.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] Agile tooling uses a cost-effective and high-quality method to quickly respond to customer and market needs, and it can be used in hydroforming, stamping, injection molding and other manufacturing processes.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] Although the terms 3D printing and additive manufacturing can both be seen as the same thing, some standards organizitons make a distinction between them.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] The American National Standards Institute (ANSI) says that international standards such as IS0/ASTM 52900 define additive manufacturing as the process of building parts from 3D model data and adding material layer by layer.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] In comparison, 3D printing is described as creating objects by depositing material through a print head or some variation of a nozzle type of device.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] In industrial and technical settings, additive manufacturing is often the preferred term, and 3D printing is used more by the general public.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] The general concept of and procedure to be used in 3D-printing was first described by Murray Leinster in his 1945 short story "Things Pass By": "But this constructor is both efficient and flexible.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] I feed magnetronic plastics — the stuff they make houses and ships of nowadays — into this moving arm.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] It makes drawings in the air following drawings it scans with photo-cells.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] Jones in his story, "Tools of the Trade", published in the November 1950 issue of *Astounding Science Fiction* magazine.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] He referred to it as a "molecular spray" in that story.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] In 1971, Johannes F Gottwald patented the Liquid Metal Recorder, U.S. patent 3596285A, a continuous inkjet metal material device to form a removable metal fabrication on a reusable surface for immediate use or salvaged for printing again by remelting.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] This appears to be the first patent describing 3D printing with rapid prototyping and controlled on-demand manufacturing of patterns.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] Jones laid out the concept of 3D printing in his regular column *Ariadne* in the journal *New Scientist*.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] Early additive manufacturing equipment and materials were developed in the 1980s.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] In April 1980, Hideo Kodama of Nagoya Municipal Industrial Research Institute invented two additive methods for fabricating three-dimensional plastic models with photo-hardening thermoset polymer, where the UV exposure area is controlled by a mask pattern or a scanning fiber transmitter.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] He filed a patent for this XYZ plotter, which was published on 10 November 1981.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] His research results as journal papers were published in April and November 1981.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] However, there was no reaction to the series of his publications.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] His device was not highly evaluated in the laboratory and his boss did not show any interest.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] His research budget was just 60,000 yen or $545 a year.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] Acquiring the patent rights for the XYZ plotter was abandoned, and the project was terminated.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] On 2 July 1984, American entrepreneur Bill Masters filed a patent for his computer automated manufacturing process and system (US 4665492).
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] This filing is on record at the USPTO as the first 3D printing patent in history; it was the first of three patents belonging to Masters that laid the foundation for the 3D printing systems used today.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] On 16 July 1984, Alain Le Méhauté, Olivier de Witte, and Jean Claude André filed their patent for the stereolithography process.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] The application of the French inventors was abandoned by the French General Electric Company (now Alcatel-Alsthom) and CILAS (The Laser Consortium).
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] The claimed reason was "for lack of business perspective".
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] Research (later named Howtek, Inc. in February 1984) to develop Pixelmaster, a color inkjet 2D printer using Thermoplastic (hot-melt) plastic ink, which was commercialized in 1986.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] A team was put together, 6 members from Exxon Office Systems, Danbury Systems Division, an inkjet printer startup and some members of Howtek, Inc group who became popular figures in the 3D printing industry.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] One Howtek member was Richard Helinski, responsible for patent US5136515A ("Method and Means for constructing three-dimensional articles by particle deposition", application 7 November 1989 granted 4 August 1992).
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] He formed C.A.D-Cast, Inc (later renamed to Visual Impact Corporation (VIC) on 22 August 1991), a New Hampshire company.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] The company's prototype VIC 3D printer is available with a video presentation showing a 3D model printed with a single nozzle inkjet.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] Another employee, Herbert Menhennett, formed HM Research, a New Hampshire company, in 1991 and introduced the Howtek, Inc, inkjet technology and thermoplastic materials to Royden Sanders of SDI and Bill Masters of Ballistic Particle Manufacturing (BPM), where he worked for a number of years.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] Both BPM 3D printers and SPI 3D printers use Howtek, Inc style Inkjets and materials.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] McMahon, who was hired by Howtek, Inc to help develop the inkjet, later worked at Sanders Prototype and now operates Layer Grown Model Technology, a 3D service provider specializing in Howtek single nozzle inkjet and SDI printer support.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] McMahon worked with Steven Zoltan, inventor of the 1972 drop-on-demand inkjet at Exxon and holder of a 1978 patent that expanded the understanding of the single nozzle design inkjets (Alpha jets), to help perfect the Howtek, Inc hot-melt inkjets.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] This Howtek hot-melt thermoplastic technology is popular with metal investment casting, especially in the 3D printing jewelry industry.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] Royden Sanders licensed the Helinksi patent prior to manufacturing the Modelmaker 6 Pro at Sanders prototype, Inc (SPI) in 1993.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] The first customer of the Modelmaker 6Pro was Hitchner Corporations, Metal Casting Technology, Inc in Milford, New Hampshire, a mile from the SDI facility in late 1993–1995 casting golf clubs and auto engine parts.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] Hull defined the process as a "system for generating three-dimensional objects by creating a cross-sectional pattern of the object to be formed".
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] Hull's contribution was the STL (Stereolithography) file format and the digital slicing and infill strategies common to many processes today.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] In 1986, Charles "Chuck" Hull was granted a patent for this system, and his company, 3D Systems Corporation was formed and it released the first commercial 3D printer, the SLA-1, later in 1987 or 1988.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] The technology used by most 3D printers to date—especially hobbyist and consumer-oriented models—is fused deposition modeling, a special application of plastic extrusion, developed in 1988 by S.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] Scott Crump and commercialized by his company Stratasys, which marketed its first FDM machine in 1992.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] AM processes for metal sintering or melting (such as selective laser sintering, direct metal laser sintering, and selective laser melting) usually went by their own individual names in the 1980s and 1990s.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] However, the automated techniques that *added* metal, which would later be called additive manufacturing, were beginning to challenge that assumption.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] By the mid-1990s, new techniques for material deposition were developed at Stanford and Carnegie Mellon University, including microcasting and sprayed materials.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] Sacrificial and support materials had also become more common, enabling new object geometries.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] The term *3D printing* originally referred to a powder bed process employing standard and custom inkjet print heads, developed at MIT by Emanuel Sachs in 1993 and commercialized by Soligen Technologies, Extrude Hone Corporation, and Z Corporation.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] The year 1993 also saw the start of an inkjet 3D printer company initially named Sanders Prototype, Inc and later named Solidscape, introducing a high-precision polymer jet fabrication system with soluble support structures, (categorized as a "dot-on-dot" technique).
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] In 1995 the Fraunhofer Society developed the selective laser melting process.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] In the early 2000s 3D printers were still largely being used just in the manufacturing and research industries, as the technology was still relatively young and was too expensive for most consumers to be able to get their hands on.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] The 2000s was when larger scale use of the technology began being seen in industry, most often in the architecture and medical industries, though it was typically used for low accuracy modeling and testing, rather than the production of common manufactured goods or heavy prototyping.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] In 2005 users began to design and distribute plans for 3D printers that could print around 70% of their own parts, the original plans of which were designed by Adrian Bowyer at the University of Bath in 2004, with the name of the project being RepRap (Replicating Rapid-prototyper).
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] Similarly, in 2006 the Fab@Home project was started by Evan Malone and Hod Lipson, another project whose purpose was to design a low-cost and open source fabrication system that users could develop on their own and post feedback on, making the project very collaborative.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] Much of the software for 3D printing available to the public at the time was open source, and as such was quickly distributed and improved upon by many individual users.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] In 2009 the Fused Deposition Modeling (FDM) printing process patents expired.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] This opened the door to a new wave of startup companies, many of which were established by major contributors of these open source initiatives, with the goal of many of them being to start developing commercial FDM 3D printers that were more accessible to the general public.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] As the various additive processes matured, it became clear that soon metal removal would no longer be the only metalworking process done through a tool or head moving through a 3D work envelope, transforming a mass of raw material into a desired shape layer by layer.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] The 2010s were the first decade in which metal end-use parts such as engine brackets and large nuts would be grown (either before or instead of machining) in job production rather than obligately being machined from bar stock or plate.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] One place that AM is making a significant inroad is in the aviation industry.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] With nearly 3.8 billion air travelers in 2016, the demand for fuel efficient and easily produced jet engines has never been higher.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] One example of AM integration with aerospace was in 2016 when Airbus delivered the first of GE's LEAP engines.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] This engine has integrated 3D-printed fuel nozzles, reducing parts from 20 to 1, a 25% weight reduction, and reduced assembly times.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] A fuel nozzle is the perfect inroad for additive manufacturing in a jet engine since it allows for optimized design of the complex internals and it is a low-stress, non-rotating part.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] Similarly, in 2015, PW delivered their first AM parts in the PurePower PW1500G to Bombardier.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] Sticking to low-stress, non-rotating parts, PW selected the compressor stators and synch ring brackets to roll out this new manufacturing technology for the first time.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] While AM is still playing a small role in the total number of parts in the jet engine manufacturing process, the return on investment can already be seen by the reduction in parts, the rapid production capabilities and the "optimized design in terms of performance and cost".
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] As technology matured, several authors began to speculate that 3D printing could aid in sustainable development in the developing world.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] In 2012, Filabot developed a system for closing the loop with plastic and allows for any FDM or FFF 3D printer to be able to print with a wider range of plastics.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] Tentzeris demonstrated the first multi-material, vertically integrated printed electronics additive manufacturing platform (VIPRE) which enabled 3D printing of functional electronics operating up to 40 GHz.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] As the price of printers started to drop people interested in this technology had more access and freedom to make what they wanted.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] As of 2014, the price for commercial printers was still high with the cost being over $2,000.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] The term "3D printing" originally referred to a process that deposits a binder material onto a powder bed with inkjet printer heads layer by layer.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] More recently, the popular vernacular has started using the term to encompass a wider variety of additive-manufacturing techniques such as electron-beam additive manufacturing and selective laser melting.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] The United States and global technical standards use the official term *additive manufacturing* for this broader sense.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] The most commonly used 3D printing process (46% as of 2018) is a material extrusion technique called fused deposition modeling, or FDM.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] While FDM technology was invented after the other two most popular technologies, stereolithography (SLA) and selective laser sintering (SLS), FDM is typically the most inexpensive of the three by a large margin, which lends to the popularity of the process.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] As of 2020, 3D printers have reached the level of quality and price that allows most people to enter the world of 3D printing.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] In 2020 decent quality printers can be found for less than US$200 for entry-level machines.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] These more affordable printers are usually fused deposition modeling (FDM) printers.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] In November 2021 a British patient named Steve Verze received the world's first fully 3D-printed prosthetic eye from the Moorfields Eye Hospital in London.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] In April 2024, the world's largest 3D printer, the Factory of the Future 1.0 was revealed at the University of Maine.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] It is able to make objects 96 feet long, or 29 meters.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] In 2024, researchers used machine learning to improve the construction of synthetic bone and set a record for shock absorption.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] In July 2024, researchers published a paper in *Advanced Materials Technologies* describing the development of artificial blood vessels using 3D-printing technology, which are as strong and durable as natural blood vessels.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] The process involved using a rotating spindle integrated into a 3D printer to create grafts from a water-based gel, which were then coated in biodegradable polyester molecules.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] In October 2025, the North Bristol NHS Trust reported that a UK cyclist named Dave Richards had received a full-face 3D-printed prosthesis, created at the newly opened Bristol 3D Medical Center at North Bristol NHS Trust.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] Led by senior reconstructive scientist Amy Davey, the process used advanced scanning and medical-grade resins to replicate his facial features after severe burns.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] It marked a milestone in integrated medical 3D-printing facilities in the UK.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] Additive manufacturing or 3D printing has rapidly gained importance in the field of engineering due to its many benefits.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] The vision of 3D printing is design freedom, individualization, decentralization and executing processes that were previously impossible through alternative methods.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] Some of these benefits include enabling faster prototyping, reducing manufacturing costs, increasing product customization, and improving product quality.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] Furthermore, the capabilities of 3D printing have extended beyond traditional manufacturing, like lightweight construction, or repair and maintenance with applications in prosthetics, bioprinting, food industry, rocket building, design and art and renewable energy systems.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] 3D printing technology can be used to produce battery energy storage systems, which are essential for sustainable energy generation and distribution.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] Another benefit of 3D printing is the technology's ability to produce complex geometries with high precision and accuracy.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] This is particularly relevant in the field of microwave engineering, where 3D printing can be used to produce components with unique properties that are difficult to achieve using traditional manufacturing methods.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] Additive Manufacturing processes generate minimal waste by adding material only where needed, unlike traditional methods that cut away excess material.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] This reduces both material costs and environmental impact.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] This reduction in waste also lowers energy consumption for material production and disposal, contributing to a smaller carbon footprint.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] 3D printable models may be created with a computer-aided design (CAD) package, via a 3D scanner, or by a plain digital camera and photogrammetry software.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] 3D printed models created with CAD result in relatively fewer errors than other methods.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] Errors in 3D printable models can be identified and corrected before printing.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] The manual modeling process of preparing geometric data for 3D computer graphics is similar to plastic arts such as sculpting.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] 3D scanning is a process of collecting digital data on the shape and appearance of a real object, and creating a digital model based on it.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] CAD models can be saved in the stereolithography file format (STL), a de facto CAD file format for additive manufacturing that stores data based on triangulations of the surface of CAD models.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] STL is not tailored for additive manufacturing because it generates large file sizes of topology-optimized parts and lattice structures due to the large number of surfaces involved.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] A newer CAD file format, the additive manufacturing file format (AMF), was introduced in 2011 to solve this problem.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] It stores information using curved triangulations.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] Before printing a 3D model from an STL file, it must first be examined for errors.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] A step in the STL generation known as "repair" fixes such problems in the original model.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] Generally, STLs that have been produced from a model obtained through 3D scanning often have more of these errors as 3D scanning is often achieved by point to point acquisition/mapping.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] 3D reconstruction often includes errors.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] Once completed, the STL file needs to be processed by a piece of software called a "slicer", which converts the model into a series of thin layers and produces a G-code file containing instructions tailored to a specific type of 3D printer.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] For instance FDM printers use FDM file formats.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] This G-code file can then be printed with 3D printing client software (which loads the G-code and uses it to instruct the 3D printer during the 3D printing process).
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] Printer resolution describes layer thickness and X–Y resolution in dots per inch (dpi) or micrometers (μm).
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] Typical layer thickness is around 100 μm (250 DPI), although some machines can print layers as thin as 16 μm (1,600 DPI).
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] X–Y resolution is comparable to that of laser printers.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] For that printer resolution, specifying a mesh resolution of 0.01–0.03 mm and a chord length ≤ 0.016 mm generates an optimal STL output file for a given model input file.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] Specifying higher resolution results in larger files without increase in print quality.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] Construction of a model with contemporary methods can take anywhere from several hours to several days, depending on the method used and the size and complexity of the model.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] Additive systems can typically reduce this time to a few hours, although it varies widely depending on the type of machine used and the size and number of models being produced simultaneously.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] Though the printer-produced resolution and surface finish are sufficient for some applications, post-processing and finishing methods allow for benefits such as greater dimensional accuracy, smoother surfaces, and other modifications such as coloration.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] The surface finish of a 3D-printed part can improved using subtractive methods such as sanding and bead blasting.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] When smoothing parts that require dimensional accuracy, it is important to take into account the volume of the material being removed.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] Some printable polymers, such as acrylonitrile butadiene styrene (ABS), allow the surface finish to be smoothed and improved using chemical vapor processes based on acetone or similar solvents.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] Some additive manufacturing techniques can benefit from annealing as a post-processing step.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] Annealing a 3D-printed part allows for better internal layer bonding due to recrystallization of the part.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] It allows for an increase in mechanical properties, some of which are fracture toughness, flexural strength, impact resistance, and heat resistance.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] Annealing a component may not be suitable for applications where dimensional accuracy is required, as it can introduce warpage or shrinkage due to heating and cooling.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] Some additively manufactured parts—especially parts that are mission critical—are post-processed with hot isostatic pressing to improve the density and to configure the microstructure to get the required mechanical performance of the printed parts.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] Additive or subtractive hybrid manufacturing (ASHM) is a method that involves producing a 3D printed part and using machining (subtractive manufacturing) to remove material.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] Machining operations can be completed after each layer, or after the entire 3D print has been completed depending on the application requirements.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] These hybrid methods allow for 3D-printed parts to achieve better surface finishes and dimensional accuracy.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] The layered structure of traditional additive manufacturing processes leads to a stair-stepping effect on part-surfaces that are curved or tilted with respect to the building platform.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] The effect strongly depends on the layer height used, as well as the orientation of a part surface inside the building process.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] This effect can be minimized using "variable layer heights" or "adaptive layer heights".
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] These methods decrease the layer height in places where higher quality is needed.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] Painting a 3D-printed part offers a range of finishes and appearances that may not be achievable through most 3D printing techniques.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] The process typically involves several steps, such as surface preparation, priming, and painting.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] These steps help prepare the surface of the part and ensuring the paint adheres properly.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] Some additive manufacturing techniques are capable of using multiple materials simultaneously.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] These techniques are able to print in multiple colors and color combinations simultaneously and can produce parts that may not necessarily require painting.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] Some printing techniques require internal supports to be built to support overhanging features during construction.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] These supports must be mechanically removed or dissolved if using a water-soluble support material such as PVA after completing a print.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] Some commercial metal 3D printers involve cutting the metal component off the metal substrate after deposition.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] A new process for the GMAW 3D printing allows for substrate surface modifications to remove aluminium or steel.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] Traditionally, 3D printing focused on polymers for printing, due to the ease of manufacturing and handling polymeric materials.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] However, the method has rapidly evolved to not only print various polymers but also metals, chocolates, and ceramics, making 3D printing a versatile option for manufacturing.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] Layer-by-layer fabrication of three-dimensional physical models is a modern concept that "stems from the ever-growing CAD industry, more specifically the solid modeling side of CAD.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] Before solid modeling was introduced in the late 1980s, three-dimensional models were created with wire frames and surfaces." but in all cases the layers of materials are controlled by the printer and the material properties.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] The three-dimensional material layer is controlled by the deposition rate as set by the printer operator and stored in a computer file.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] The earliest printed patented material was a hot melt type ink for printing patterns using a heated metal alloy.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] Charles Hull filed the first patent on August 8, 1984, to use a UV-cured acrylic resin using a UV-masked light source at UVP Corp to build a simple model.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] The SLA-1 was the first SL product announced by 3D Systems at Autofact Exposition, Detroit, November 1978.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] The SLA-1 Beta shipped in Jan 1988 to Baxter Healthcare, Pratt and Whitney, General Motors and AMP.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] The first production SLA-1 shipped to Precision Castparts in April 1988.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] The UV resin material changed over quickly to an epoxy-based material resin.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] In both cases, SLA-1 models needed UV oven curing after being rinsed in a solvent cleaner to remove uncured boundary resin.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] A post cure apparatus (PCA) was sold with all systems.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] The early resin printers required a blade to move fresh resin over the model on each layer.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] The layer thickness was 0.006 inches and the HeCd laser model of the SLA-1 was 12 watts and swept across the surface at 30 inch per second.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] UVP was acquired by 3D Systems in January 1990.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] A review of the history shows that a number of materials (resins, plastic powder, plastic filament and hot-melt plastic ink) were used in the 1980s for patents in the rapid prototyping field.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] Masked lamp UV-cured resin was also introduced by Cubital's Itzchak Pomerantz in the Soldier 5600, Carl Deckard's (DTM) laser sintered thermoplastic powders, and adhesive-laser cut paper (LOM) stacked to form objects by Michael Feygin before 3D Systems made its first announcement.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] The most common polymers for personal 3D printers are polylactic acid (PLA) and PETG.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] Efforts to achieve multi-material 3D printing range from enhanced FDM-like processes like VoxelJet to novel voxel-based printing technologies like layered assembly.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] A drawback of many existing 3D printing technologies is that they only allow one material to be printed at a time, limiting many potential applications that require the integration of different materials in the same object.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] Multi-material 3D printing solves this problem by allowing objects of complex and heterogeneous arrangements of materials to be manufactured using a single printer.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] Here, a material must be specified for each voxel (or 3D printing pixel element) inside the final object volume.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] The process can be fraught with complications, however, due to the isolated and monolithic algorithms.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] Some commercial devices have sought to solve these issues, such as building a Spec2Fab translator, but the progress is still very limited.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] Nonetheless, in the medical industry, a concept of 3D-printed pills and vaccines has been presented.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] With this new concept, multiple medications can be combined, which is expected to decrease many risks.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] With more and more applications of multi-material 3D printing, the costs of daily life and high technology development will become inevitably lower.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] Metallographic materials of 3D printing is also being researched.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] By classifying each material, CIMP-3D can systematically perform 3D printing with multiple materials.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] Using 3D printing and multi-material structures in additive manufacturing has allowed for the design and creation of what is called 4D printing.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] 4D printing is an additive manufacturing process in which the printed object changes shape with time, temperature, or some other type of stimulation.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] 4D printing allows for the creation of dynamic structures with adjustable shapes, properties or functionality.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] The smart/stimulus-responsive materials that are created using 4D printing can be activated to create calculated responses such as self-assembly, self-repair, multi-functionality, reconfiguration and shape-shifting.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] This allows for customized printing of shape-changing and shape-memory materials.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] 4D printing has the potential to find new applications and uses for materials (plastics, composites, metals, etc.) and has the potential to create new alloys and composites that were not viable before.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] The versatility of this technology and materials can lead to advances in multiple fields of industry, including space, commercial and medical fields.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] The repeatability, precision, and material range for 4D printing must increase to allow the process to become more practical throughout these industries.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] To become a viable industrial production option, there are a few challenges that 4D printing must overcome.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] The challenges of 4D printing include the fact that the microstructures of these printed smart materials must be close to or better than the parts obtained through traditional machining processes.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] New and customizable materials need to be developed that have the ability to consistently respond to varying external stimuli and change to their desired shape.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] There is also a need to design new software for the various technique types of 4D printing.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] The 4D printing software will need to take into consideration the base smart material, printing technique, and structural and geometric requirements of the design.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] A variety of processes, equipment, and materials are used in the production of a three-dimensional object via additive manufacturing.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p01] Techniques include jetting, extrusion, additive friction stir deposition, powder bed fusion, binder jetting, stereolithography, computed axial lithography, liquid alternative, lamination, directed energy deposition, selective powder deposition, and cryogenic manufacturing.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] 3D printing or additive manufacturing has been used in manufacturing, medical, industry and sociocultural sectors (e.g. cultural heritage) to create successful commercial technology.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] More recently, 3D printing has also been used in the humanitarian and development sector to produce a range of medical items, prosthetics, spares and repairs.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] The earliest application of additive manufacturing was on the toolroom end of the manufacturing spectrum.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] For example, rapid prototyping was one of the earliest additive variants, and its mission was to reduce the lead time and cost of developing prototypes of new parts and devices, which was earlier only done with subtractive toolroom methods such as CNC milling, turning, and precision grinding.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] In the 2010s, additive manufacturing entered production to a much greater extent.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] Additive manufacturing of food is being developed by squeezing out food, layer by layer, into three-dimensional objects.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] A large variety of foods are appropriate candidates, such as chocolate and candy, and flat foods such as crackers, pasta, and pizza.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] NASA is looking into the technology in order to create 3D-printed food to limit food waste and to make food that is designed to fit an astronaut's dietary needs.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] In 2018, Italian bioengineer Giuseppe Scionti developed a technology allowing the production of fibrous plant-based meat analogues using a custom 3D bioprinter, mimicking meat texture and nutritional values.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] 3D printing has entered the world of clothing, with fashion designers experimenting with 3D-printed bikinis, shoes, and dresses.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] In commercial production, Nike used 3D printing to prototype and manufacture the 2012 Vapor Laser Talon football shoe for players of American football, and New Balance has 3D manufactured custom-fit shoes for athletes.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] 3D printing has come to the point where companies are printing consumer-grade eyewear with on-demand custom fit and styling (although they cannot print the lenses).
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] On-demand customization of glasses is possible with rapid prototyping.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] Armor-design strategies can be enhanced by taking inspiration from nature and prototyping those designs using AM.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] In cars, trucks, and aircraft, additive manufacturing is beginning to transform both unibody and fuselage design and production, and powertrain design and production.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] For example, General Electric uses high-end 3D printers to build parts for turbines.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] Many of these systems are used for rapid prototyping before mass production methods are employed.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] AM's impact on firearms involves two dimensions: new manufacturing methods for established companies, and new possibilities for the making of do-it-yourself firearms.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] In 2012, the US-based group Defense Distributed disclosed plans to design a working plastic 3D-printed firearm "that could be downloaded and reproduced by anybody with a 3D printer".
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] After Defense Distributed released their plans, questions were raised regarding the effects that 3D printing and widespread consumer-level CNC machining may have on gun control effectiveness.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] Surgical uses of 3D printing-centric therapies began in the mid-1990s with anatomical modeling for bony reconstructive surgery planning.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] Patient-matched implants were a natural extension of this work, leading to truly personalized implants that fit one unique individual.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] Virtual planning of surgery and guidance using 3D printed, personalized instruments have been applied to many areas of surgery including total joint replacement and craniomaxillofacial reconstruction with great success.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] One example of this is the bioresorbable trachial splint to treat newborns with tracheobronchomalacia developed at the University of Michigan.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] The use of additive manufacturing for serialized production of orthopedic implants (metals) is also increasing due to the ability to efficiently create porous surface structures that facilitate osseointegration.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] The hearing aid and dental industries are expected to be the biggest areas of future development using custom 3D printing technology.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] 3D printing is not just limited to inorganic materials; there have been a number of biomedical advancements made possible by 3D printing.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] As of 2012, 3D bio-printing technology has been studied by biotechnology firms and academia for possible use in tissue engineering applications in which organs and body parts are built using inkjet printing techniques.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] In this process, layers of living cells are deposited onto a gel medium or sugar matrix and slowly built up to form three-dimensional structures including vascular systems.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] 3D printing has been considered as a method of implanting stem cells capable of generating new tissues and organs in living humans.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] In 2018, 3D printing technology was used for the first time to create a matrix for cell immobilization in fermentation.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] Propionic acid production by *Propionibacterium acidipropionici* immobilized on 3D-printed nylon beads was chosen as a model study.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] It was shown that those 3D-printed beads were capable of promoting high-density cell attachment and propionic acid production, which could be adapted to other fermentation bioprocesses.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] 3D printing has also been employed by researchers in the pharmaceutical field.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] During the last few years, there has been a surge in academic interest regarding drug delivery with the aid of AM techniques.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] This technology offers a unique way for materials to be utilized in novel formulations.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] AM manufacturing allows for the usage of materials and compounds in the development of formulations, in ways that are not possible with conventional/traditional techniques in the pharmaceutical field, e.g. tableting, cast-molding, etc.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] Moreover, one of the major advantages of 3D printing, especially in the case of fused deposition modelling (FDM), is the personalization of the dosage form that can be achieved, thus, targeting the patient's specific needs.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] In the not-so-distant future, 3D printers are expected to reach hospitals and pharmacies in order to provide on-demand production of personalized formulations according to the patients' needs.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] 3D printing has also been used for medical equipment.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] During the COVID-19 pandemic 3D printers were used to supplement the strained supply of PPE through volunteers using their personally owned printers to produce various pieces of personal protective equipment (i.e. frames for face shields).
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] 3D printing, and open source 3D printers, in particular, are the latest technologies making inroads into the classroom.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] Higher education has proven to be a major buyer of desktop and professional 3D printers which industry experts generally view as a positive indicator.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] Some authors have claimed that 3D printers offer an unprecedented "revolution" in STEM education.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] The evidence for such claims comes from both the low-cost ability for rapid prototyping in the classroom by students, but also the fabrication of low-cost high-quality scientific equipment from open hardware designs forming open-source labs.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] Additionally, Libraries around the world have also become locations to house smaller 3D printers for educational and community access.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] Future applications for 3D printing might include creating open-source scientific equipment.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] In the 2010s, 3D printing became intensively used in the cultural heritage field for preservation, restoration and dissemination purposes.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] Many Europeans and North American Museums have purchased 3D printers and actively recreate missing pieces of their relics and archaeological monuments such as Tiwanaku in Bolivia.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] The Metropolitan Museum of Art and the British Museum have started using their 3D printers to create museum souvenirs that are available in the museum shops.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] Other museums, like the National Museum of Military History and Varna Historical Museum, have gone further and sell through the online platform Threeding digital models of their artifacts, created using Artec 3D scanners, in 3D printing friendly file format, which everyone can 3D print at home.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] Morehshin Allahyari, an Iranian-born U.S. artist, considers her use of 3D sculpting processes of re-constructing Iranian cultural treasures as feminist activism.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] Allahyari uses a 3D modeling software to reconstruct a series of cultural artifacts that were demolished by ISIS militants in 2014.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] The application of 3D printing for the representation of architectural assets has many challenges.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] In 2018, the structure of Iran National Bank was traditionally surveyed and modeled in computer graphics software (specifically, Cinema4D) and was optimized for 3D printing.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] The team tested the technique for the construction of the part and it was successful.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] After testing the procedure, the modellers reconstructed the structure in Cinema4D and exported the front part of the model to Netfabb.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] The entrance of the building was chosen due to the 3D printing limitations and the budget of the project for producing the maquette.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] 3D printing was only one of the capabilities enabled by the produced 3D model of the bank, but due to the project's limited scope, the team did not continue modelling for the virtual representation or other applications.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] In 2021, Parsinejad et al. comprehensively compared the hand surveying method for 3D reconstruction ready for 3D printing with digital recording (adoption of photogrammetry method).
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] The world's first 3D-printed steel bridge was unveiled in Amsterdam in July 2021.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] Spanning 12 meters over the Oudezijds Achterburgwal canal, the bridge was created using robotic arms that printed over 4,500 kilograms of stainless steel.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] 3D printed soft actuators is a growing application of 3D printing technology that has found its place in the 3D printing applications.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] These soft actuators are being developed to deal with soft structures and organs, especially in biomedical sectors and where the interaction between humans and robots is inevitable.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] The majority of the existing soft actuators are fabricated by conventional methods that require manual fabrication of devices, post-processing/assembly, and lengthy iterations until the maturity of the fabrication is achieved.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] Instead of the tedious and time-consuming aspects of the current fabrication processes, researchers are exploring an appropriate manufacturing approach for the effective fabrication of soft actuators.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] Thus, 3D-printed soft actuators are introduced to revolutionize the design and fabrication of soft actuators with custom geometrical, functional, and control properties in a faster and inexpensive approach.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] They also enable incorporation of all actuator components into a single structure eliminating the need to use external joints, adhesives, and fasteners.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] Circuit board manufacturing involves multiple steps which include imaging, drilling, plating, solder mask coating, nomenclature printing and surface finishes.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] These steps include many chemicals such as harsh solvents and acids.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] 3D printing circuit boards remove the need for many of these steps while still producing complex designs.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] Polymer ink is used to create the layers of the build while silver polymer is used for creating the traces and holes used to allow electricity to flow.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] Current circuit board manufacturing can be a tedious process depending on the design.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] Specified materials are gathered and sent into inner layer processing where images are printed, developed and etched.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] The etch cores are typically punched to add lamination tooling.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] The cores are then prepared for lamination.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] The stack-up, the buildup of a circuit board, is built and sent into lamination where the layers are bonded.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] The boards are then measured and drilled.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] Many steps may differ from this stage however for simple designs, the material goes through a plating process to plate the holes and surface.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] The outer image is then printed, developed and etched.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] After the image is defined, the material must get coated with a solder mask for later soldering.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] Nomenclature is then added so components can be identified later.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] The boards are routed out of panel form into their singular or array form and then electrically tested.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] Aside from the paperwork that must be completed which proves the boards meet specifications, the boards are then packed and shipped.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] The benefits of 3D printing would be that the final outline is defined from the beginning, no imaging, punching or lamination is required and electrical connections are made with the silver polymer which eliminates drilling and plating.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] The final paperwork would also be greatly reduced due to the lack of materials required to build the circuit board.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] Complex designs which may take weeks to complete through normal processing can be 3D printed, greatly reducing manufacturing time.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] In 2005, academic journals began to report on the possible artistic applications of 3D printing technology.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] Off-the-shelf machines were increasingly capable of producing practical household applications, for example, ornamental objects.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] Some practical examples include a working clock and gears printed for home woodworking machines among other purposes.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] Websites associated with home 3D printing tended to include backscratchers, coat hooks, door knobs, etc.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] As of 2017, domestic 3D printing was reaching a consumer audience beyond hobbyists and enthusiasts.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] Several projects and companies are making efforts to develop affordable 3D printers for home desktop use.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] Much of this work has been driven by and targeted at DIY/maker/enthusiast/early adopter communities, with additional ties to the academic and hacker communities.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] Sped on by decreases in price and increases in quality, As of 2019 an estimated 2 million people worldwide have purchased a 3D printer for hobby use.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] 3D printing has existed for decades within certain manufacturing industries where many legal regimes, including patents, industrial design rights, copyrights, and trademarks may apply.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] However, there is not much jurisprudence to say how these laws will apply if 3D printers become mainstream and individuals or hobbyist communities begin manufacturing items for personal use, for non-profit distribution, or for sale.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] Any of the mentioned legal regimes may prohibit the distribution of the designs used in 3D printing or the distribution or sale of the printed item.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] To be allowed to do these things, where active intellectual property was involved, a person would have to contact the owner and ask for a licence, which may come with conditions and a price.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] However, many patent, design and copyright laws contain a standard limitation or exception for "private" or "non-commercial" use of inventions, designs or works of art protected under intellectual property (IP).
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] That standard limitation or exception may leave such private, non-commercial uses outside the scope of IP rights.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] Patents cover inventions including processes, machines, manufacturing, and compositions of matter and have a finite duration which varies between countries, but generally 20 years from the date of application.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] Therefore, if a type of wheel is patented, printing, using, or selling such a wheel could be an infringement of the patent.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] Copyright covers an expression in a tangible, fixed medium and often lasts for the life of the author plus 70 years thereafter.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] For example, a sculptor retains copyright over a statue, such that other people cannot then legally distribute designs to print an identical or similar statue without paying royalties, waiting for the copyright to expire, or working within a fair use exception.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] When a feature has both artistic (copyrightable) and functional (patentable) merits when the question has appeared in US court, the courts have often held the feature is not copyrightable unless it can be separated from the functional aspects of the item.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] Attempting to restrict the distribution of gun plans via the Internet has been likened to the futility of preventing the widespread distribution of DeCSS, which enabled DVD ripping.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] After the US government had Defense Distributed take down the plans, they were still widely available via the Pirate Bay and other file sharing sites.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] Downloads of the plans from the UK, Germany, Spain, and Brazil were heavy.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] Some US legislators have proposed regulations on 3D printers to prevent them from being used for printing guns.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] 3D printing advocates have suggested that such regulations would be futile, could cripple the 3D printing industry and could infringe on free speech rights, with early pioneers of 3D printing professor Hod Lipson suggesting that gunpowder could be controlled instead.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] Internationally, where gun controls are generally stricter than in the United States, some commentators have said the impact may be more strongly felt since alternative firearms are not as easily obtainable.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] Officials in the United Kingdom have noted that producing a 3D-printed gun would be illegal under their gun control laws.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] Europol stated that criminals have access to other sources of weapons but noted that as technology improves, the risks of an effect would increase.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] In the United States, the FAA has anticipated a desire to use additive manufacturing techniques and has been considering how best to regulate this process.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] The FAA has jurisdiction over such fabrication because all aircraft parts must be made under FAA production approval or under other FAA regulatory categories.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] In December 2016, the FAA approved the production of a 3D-printed fuel nozzle for the GE LEAP engine.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] Aviation attorney Jason Dickstein has suggested that additive manufacturing is merely a production method, and should be regulated like any other production method.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] He has suggested that the FAA's focus should be on guidance to explain compliance, rather than on changing the existing rules, and that existing regulations and guidance permit a company "to develop a robust quality system that adequately reflects regulatory needs for quality assurance".
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] In 2021, first standards were issued, e.g.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] ASTM ISO/ASTM52900-21 Additive manufacturing general principles, fundamentals and vocabulary, and the above-mentioned ISO/ASTM52900-15.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] In 2023, the ISO/ASTM 52920:2023 defined the requirements for industrial additive manufacturing processes and production sites using additive manufacturing to ensure required quality level.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] Aforetime in Germany there was a draft of DIN norm issued, DIN SPEC 17071:2019.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] Polymer feedstock materials can release ultrafine particles and volatile organic compounds (VOCs) if sufficiently heated, which in combination have been associated with adverse respiratory and cardiovascular health effects.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] In addition, temperatures of 190 °C to 260 °C are typically reached by an FFF extrusion nozzle, which can cause skin burns.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] Vat photopolymerization stereolithography printers use high-powered lasers that present a skin and eye hazard, although they are considered nonhazardous during printing because the laser is enclosed within the printing chamber.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] 3D printers also contain many moving parts that include stepper motors, pulleys, threaded rods, carriages, and small fans, which generally do not have enough power to cause serious injuries but can still trap a user's finger, long hair, or loose clothing.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] Most desktop FFF 3D printers do not have any added electrical safety features beyond regular internal fuses or external transformers, although the voltages in the exposed parts of 3D printers usually do not exceed 12V to 24V, which is generally considered safe.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] Research on the health and safety concerns of 3D printing is new and in development due to the recent proliferation of 3D printing devices.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] In 2017, the European Agency for Safety and Health at Work published a discussion paper on the processes and materials involved in 3D printing, the potential implications of this technology for occupational safety and health and avenues for controlling potential hazards.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] Noise level is measured in decibels (dB), and can vary greatly in home printers from 15 dB to 75 dB.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] Some main sources of noise in filament printers are fans, motors and bearings, while in resin printers the fans usually are responsible for most of the noise.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] Some methods for dampening the noise from a printer may be to install vibration isolation, use larger diameter fans, perform regular maintenance and lubrication, or use a soundproofing enclosure.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] Additive manufacturing, starting with today's infancy period, requires manufacturing firms to be flexible, ever-improving users of all available technologies to remain competitive.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] Advocates of additive manufacturing also predict that this arc of technological development will counter globalization, as end users will do much of their own manufacturing rather than engage in trade to buy products from other people and corporations.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] The real integration of the newer additive technologies into commercial production, however, is more a matter of complementing traditional subtractive methods rather than displacing them entirely.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] The futurologist Jeremy Rifkin claimed that 3D printing signals the beginning of a third industrial revolution, succeeding the production line assembly that dominated manufacturing starting in the late 19th century.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] Since the 1950s, a number of writers and social commentators have speculated in some depth about the social and cultural changes that might result from the advent of commercially affordable additive manufacturing technology.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] In recent years, 3D printing has created a significant impact in the humanitarian and development sector.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] Its potential to facilitate distributed manufacturing is resulting in supply chain and logistics benefits, by reducing the need for transportation, warehousing and wastage.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] Furthermore, social and economic development is being advanced through the creation of local production economies.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] Others have suggested that as more and more 3D printers start to enter people's homes, the conventional relationship between the home and the workplace might get further eroded.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] Likewise, it has also been suggested that, as it becomes easier for businesses to transmit designs for new objects around the globe, so the need for high-speed freight services might also become less.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] Finally, given the ease with which certain objects can now be replicated, it remains to be seen whether changes will be made to current copyright legislation so as to protect intellectual property rights with the new technology widely available.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] Some call attention to the conjunction of commons-based peer production with 3D printing and other low-cost manufacturing techniques.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] The self-reinforced fantasy of a system of eternal growth can be overcome with the development of economies of scope, and here, society can play an important role contributing to the raising of the whole productive structure to a higher plateau of more sustainable and customized productivity.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] Further, it is true that many issues, problems, and threats arise due to the democratization of the means of production, and especially regarding the physical ones.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] For instance, the recyclability of advanced nanomaterials is still questioned; weapons manufacturing could become easier; not to mention the implications for counterfeiting and on intellectual property.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] It might be maintained that in contrast to the industrial paradigm whose competitive dynamics were about economies of scale, commons-based peer production 3D printing could develop economies of scope.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] While the advantages of scale rest on cheap global transportation, the economies of scope share infrastructure costs (intangible and tangible productive resources), taking advantage of the capabilities of the fabrication tools.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] And following Neil Gershenfeld in that "some of the least developed parts of the world need some of the most advanced technologies", commons-based peer production and 3D printing may offer the necessary tools for thinking globally but acting locally in response to certain needs.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] Larry Summers wrote about the "devastating consequences" of 3D printing and other technologies (robots, artificial intelligence, etc.) for those who perform routine tasks.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] In his view, "already there are more American men on disability insurance than doing production work in manufacturing.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] Michael Spence wrote that "Now comes a ... powerful, wave of digital technology that is replacing labor in increasingly complex tasks.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] This process of labor substitution and disintermediation has been underway for some time in service sectors—think of ATMs, online banking, enterprise resource planning, customer relationship management, mobile payment systems, and much more.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] This revolution is spreading to the production of goods, where robots and 3D printing are displacing labor." In his view, the vast majority of the cost of digital technologies comes at the start, in the design of hardware (e.g.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] 3D printers) and, more importantly, in creating the software that enables machines to carry out various tasks.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] "Once this is achieved, the marginal cost of the hardware is relatively low (and declines as scale rises), and the marginal cost of replicating the software is essentially zero.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] Spence believes that, unlike prior digital technologies, which drove firms to deploy underutilized pools of valuable labor around the world, the motivating force in the current wave of digital technologies "is cost reduction via the replacement of labor".
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] For example, as the cost of 3D printing technology declines, it is "easy to imagine" that production may become "extremely" local and customized.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] Moreover, production may occur in response to actual demand, not anticipated or forecast demand.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] Spence believes that labor, no matter how inexpensive, will become a less important asset for growth and employment expansion, with labor-intensive, process-oriented manufacturing becoming less effective, and that re-localization will appear in both developed and developing countries.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] In his view, production will not disappear, but it will be less labor-intensive, and all countries will eventually need to rebuild their growth models around digital technologies and the human capital supporting their deployment and expansion.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] Spence writes that "the world we are entering is one in which the most powerful global flows will be ideas and digital capital, not goods, services, and traditional capital.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] Naomi Wu regards the usage of 3D printing in the Chinese classroom (where rote memorization is standard) to teach design principles and creativity as the most exciting recent development of the technology, and more generally regards 3D printing as being the next desktop publishing revolution.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] A printer was donated to the Juan Fernandez Women's Group in 2024, to support women in the remote community to be able to create parts to fix broken equipment, without having to wait for a ship to import the needed components.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] The growth of additive manufacturing could have a large impact on the environment.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] Traditional subtractive manufacturing methods such as CNC milling create products by cutting away material from a larger block.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] In contrast, additive manufacturing creates products layer-by layer, using the minimum required materials to create the product.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] This has the benefit of reducing material waste, which further contributes to energy savings by avoiding raw material production.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] Life-cycle assessment of additive manufacturing has estimated that adopting the technology could further lower carbon dioxide emissions since 3D printing creates localized production, thus reducing the need to transport products and the emissions associated.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] AM could also allow consumers to create their own replacement parts to fix purchased products to extend the lifespan of purchased products.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] By making only the bare structural necessities of products, additive manufacturing also has the potential to make profound contributions to lightweighting.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] The use of these lightweight components would allow for reductions in the energy consumption and greenhouse gas emissions of vehicles and other forms of transportation.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] A case study on an airplane component made using additive manufacturing, for example, found that the use of the component saves 63% of relevant energy and carbon dioxide emissions over the course of the product's lifetime.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] However, the adoption of additive manufacturing also has environmental disadvantages.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] Firstly, AM has a high energy consumption compared to traditional processes.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] This is due to its use of processes such as lasers and high temperatures for product creation.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] Secondly, despite additive manufacturing reducing up to 90% of waste compared to subtractive manufacturing, AM can generate waste that is non-recyclable.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] For example, there are issues with the recyclability of materials in metal AM as some highly regulated industries such as aerospace often insist on using virgin powder in the creation of safety critical components.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] Additive manufacturing has not yet reached its theoretical material efficiency potential of 97%, but it may get closer as the technology continues to increase productivity.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] Despite the drawbacks, research and industry are making further strides to support AM's sustainability.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] Some large FDM printers that melt high-density polyethylene (HDPE) pellets may also accept sufficiently clean recycled material such as chipped milk bottles.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] In addition, these printers can use shredded material from faulty builds or unsuccessful prototype versions, thus reducing overall project wastage and materials handling and storage.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] The concept has been explored in the RecycleBot.
[src:coating/3-d-printing-p02] There are also industrial efforts to produce metal powder from recycled metals.
[src:coating/adhesion-tester] In the paint and coating industries, **paint adhesion testing** is often used to determine if the paint or coating will adhere properly to the substrates to which they are applied.
[src:coating/adhesion-tester] Several tests measure the resistance of paints and coatings from substrates: cross-cut test, scrape adhesion, pull-off test, and others.
[src:coating/adhesion-tester] The scrape adhesion test measures the determination of the adhesion of organic coatings when applied to smooth, flat panel surfaces.
[src:coating/adhesion-tester] It is helpful in giving relative ratings for a number of coated panels showing significant differences in adhesion.
[src:coating/adhesion-tester] The tested materials are applied uniformly to flat panels, mainly some sort of sheet metal.
[src:coating/adhesion-tester] When the materials have dried, the adhesion is determined by pressing panels under a rounded stylus loaded with increasing weight until the coating is removed from the substrate surface.
[src:coating/adhesion-tester] The adhesion of a coating or several coated samples of any paint product is measured by assessing the minimum tensile stress needed to detach or rupture the coating perpendicular to the substrate.
[src:coating/adhesion-tester] Unlike the other methods, this method maximizes the tensile stress, therefore, results may not be comparable.
[src:coating/adhesion-tester] The test is done by securing loading fixtures (dollies) perpendicular to the surface of a coating with an adhesive.
[src:coating/adhesion-tester] Then the testing apparatus is attached to the loading fixture and aligned to apply tension perpendicular to the test surface.
[src:coating/adhesion-tester] The force that is applied gradually increases and is monitored until a plug of coating is detached or a previously specified value is reached.
[src:coating/adhesion-tester] The cross-cut test is a method for determining the resistance of paints and coatings to separation from substrates by utilizing a tool to cut a right-angle lattice pattern into the coating, penetrating to the substrate.
[src:coating/adhesion-tester] A quick pass/fail test can be accomplished through this method.
[src:coating/adhesion-tester] When testing a multi-coat system, determination of the resistance to separating different layers from one another can be accomplished.
[src:coating/adhesion-tester] An X-cut is made through the film with a carbide tip tool to the substrate.
[src:coating/adhesion-tester] Pressure-sensitive tape is applied over the cut.
[src:coating/adhesion-tester] Tape is smoothed into place using a pencil eraser over the area of the incisions.
[src:coating/adhesion-tester] Tape is removed by pulling it off rapidly back over itself as close to an angle of 180°.
[src:coating/adhesion-tester] A crosshatch pattern is made through the film to the substrate.
[src:coating/adhesion-tester] Detached flakes of coating are removed by brushing with a soft brush.
[src:coating/adhesion-tester] Pressure-sensitive tape is applied over the crosshatch cut.
[src:coating/adhesion] The forces that cause adhesion and cohesion can be divided into several types.
[src:coating/adhesion] The intermolecular forces responsible for the function of various kinds of stickers and sticky tape fall into the categories of chemical adhesion, dispersive adhesion, and diffusive adhesion.
[src:coating/adhesion] In addition to the cumulative magnitudes of these intermolecular forces, there are also certain emergent mechanical effects.
[src:coating/adhesion] Surface energy is conventionally defined as the work that is required to build an area of a particular surface.
[src:coating/adhesion] Another way to view the surface energy is to relate it to the work required to cleave a bulk sample, creating two surfaces.
[src:coating/adhesion] If the new surfaces are identical, the surface energy γ of each surface is equal to half the work of cleavage, W: γ = (1/2)W11.
[src:coating/adhesion] If the surfaces are unequal, the Young-Dupré equation applies: W12 = γ1 + γ2 – γ12, where γ1 and γ2 are the surface energies of the two new surfaces, and γ12 is the interfacial energy.
[src:coating/adhesion] This methodology can also be used to discuss cleavage that happens in another medium: γ12 = (1/2)W121 = (1/2)W212.
[src:coating/adhesion] These two energy quantities refer to the energy that is needed to cleave one species into two pieces while it is contained in a medium of the other species.
[src:coating/adhesion] Likewise for a three species system: γ13 + γ23 – γ12 = W12 + W33 – W13 – W23 = W132, where W132 is the energy of cleaving species 1 from species 2 in a medium of species 3.
[src:coating/adhesion] There is no single theory covering adhesion, and particular mechanisms are specific to particular material scenarios.
[src:coating/adhesion] Adhesive materials fill the voids or pores of the surfaces and hold surfaces together by interlocking.
[src:coating/adhesion] Other interlocking phenomena are observed on different length scales.
[src:coating/adhesion] Sewing is an example of two materials forming a large scale mechanical bond, velcro forms one on a medium scale, and some textile adhesives (glue) form one at a small scale.
[src:coating/adhesion] Two materials may form a compound at the joint.
[src:coating/adhesion] The strongest joints are where atoms of the two materials share or swap electrons (known respectively as covalent bonding or ionic bonding).
[src:coating/adhesion] A weaker bond is formed if a hydrogen atom in one molecule is attracted to an atom of nitrogen, oxygen, or fluorine in another molecule, a phenomenon called hydrogen bonding.
[src:coating/adhesion] Chemical adhesion occurs when the surface atoms of two separate surfaces form ionic, covalent, or hydrogen bonds.
[src:coating/adhesion] The engineering principle behind chemical adhesion in this sense is fairly straightforward: if surface molecules can bond, then the surfaces will be bonded together by a network of these bonds.
[src:coating/adhesion] It bears mentioning that these attractive ionic and covalent forces are effective over only very small distances – less than a nanometer.
[src:coating/adhesion] This means in general not only that surfaces with the potential for chemical bonding need to be brought very close together, but also that these bonds are fairly brittle, since the surfaces then need to be kept close together.
[src:coating/adhesion] In dispersive adhesion, also known as physisorption, two materials are held together by van der Waals forces: the attraction between two molecules, each of which has a region of slight positive and negative charge.
[src:coating/adhesion] In the simple case, such molecules are therefore polar with respect to average charge density, although in larger or more complex molecules, there may be multiple "poles" or regions of greater positive or negative charge.
[src:coating/adhesion] These positive and negative poles may be a permanent property of a molecule (Keesom forces) or a transient effect which can occur in any molecule, as the random movement of electrons within the molecules may result in a temporary concentration of electrons in one region (London forces).
[src:coating/adhesion] In surface science, the term *adhesion* almost always refers to dispersive adhesion.
[src:coating/adhesion] In a typical solid-liquid-gas system (such as a drop of liquid on a solid surrounded by air) the contact angle is used to evaluate adhesiveness indirectly, while a Centrifugal Adhesion Balance allows for direct quantitative adhesion measurements.
[src:coating/adhesion] Generally, cases where the contact angle is low are considered of higher adhesion per unit area.
[src:coating/adhesion] This approach assumes that the lower contact angle corresponds to a higher surface energy.
[src:coating/adhesion] Theoretically, the more exact relation between contact angle and work of adhesion is more involved and is given by the Young-Dupre equation.
[src:coating/adhesion] The contact angle of the three-phase system is a function not only of dispersive adhesion (interaction between the molecules in the liquid and the molecules in the solid) but also cohesion (interaction between the liquid molecules themselves).
[src:coating/adhesion] Strong adhesion and weak cohesion results in a high degree of wetting, a lyophilic condition with low measured contact angles.
[src:coating/adhesion] Conversely, weak adhesion and strong cohesion results in lyophobic conditions with high measured contact angles and poor wetting.
[src:coating/adhesion] London dispersion forces are particularly useful for the function of adhesive devices, because they do not require either surface to have any permanent polarity.
[src:coating/adhesion] They were described in the 1930s by Fritz London, and have been observed by many researchers.
[src:coating/adhesion] Dispersive forces are a consequence of statistical quantum mechanics.
[src:coating/adhesion] London theorized that attractive forces between molecules that cannot be explained by ionic or covalent interaction can be caused by polar moments within molecules.
[src:coating/adhesion] Multipoles could account for attraction between molecules having permanent multipole moments that participate in electrostatic interaction.
[src:coating/adhesion] However, experimental data showed that many of the compounds observed to experience van der Waals forces had no multipoles at all.
[src:coating/adhesion] London suggested that momentary dipoles are induced purely by virtue of molecules being in proximity to one another.
[src:coating/adhesion] While the first term is simply the zero-point energy, the negative second term describes an attractive force between neighboring oscillators.
[src:coating/adhesion] The same argument can also be extended to a large number of coupled oscillators, and thus skirts issues that would negate the large scale attractive effects of permanent dipoles cancelling through symmetry, in particular.
[src:coating/adhesion] The additive nature of the dispersion effect has another useful consequence.
[src:coating/adhesion] Consider a single such dispersive dipole, referred to as the origin dipole.
[src:coating/adhesion] When considering identical particles, this is called cohesive force.
[src:coating/adhesion] When discussing adhesion, this theory needs to be converted into terms relating to surfaces.
[src:coating/adhesion] If there is a net attractive energy of cohesion in a bulk of similar molecules, then cleaving this bulk to produce two surfaces will yield surfaces with a dispersive surface energy, since the form of the energy remain the same.
[src:coating/adhesion] This theory provides a basis for the existence of van der Waals forces at the surface, which exist between any molecules having electrons.
[src:coating/adhesion] These forces are easily observed through the spontaneous jumping of smooth surfaces into contact.
[src:coating/adhesion] Smooth surfaces of mica, gold, various polymers and solid gelatin solutions do not stay apart when their separating becomes small enough – on the order of 1–10 nm.
[src:coating/adhesion] where P is the force (negative for attraction), z is the separation distance, and A is a material-specific constant called the Hamaker constant.
[src:coating/adhesion] The effect is also apparent in experiments where a polydimethylsiloxane (PDMS) stamp is made with small periodic post structures.
[src:coating/adhesion] The surface with the posts is placed face down on a smooth surface, such that the surface area in between each post is elevated above the smooth surface, like a roof supported by columns.
[src:coating/adhesion] Because of these attractive dispersive forces between the PDMS and the smooth substrate, the elevated surface – or "roof" – collapses down onto the substrate without any external force aside from the van der Waals attraction.
[src:coating/adhesion] Simple smooth polymer surfaces – without any microstructures – are commonly used for these dispersive adhesive properties.
[src:coating/adhesion] Decals and stickers that adhere to glass without using any chemical adhesives are fairly common as toys and decorations and useful as removable labels because they do not rapidly lose their adhesive properties, as do sticky tapes that use adhesive chemical compounds.
[src:coating/adhesion] These forces also act over very small distances – 99% of the work necessary to break van der Waals bonds is done once surfaces are pulled more than a nanometer apart.
[src:coating/adhesion] As a result of this limited motion in both the van der Waals and ionic/covalent bonding situations, practical effectiveness of adhesion due to either or both of these interactions leaves much to be desired.
[src:coating/adhesion] Once a crack is initiated, it propagates easily along the interface because of the brittle nature of the interfacial bonds.
[src:coating/adhesion] As an additional consequence, increasing surface area often does little to enhance the strength of the adhesion in this situation.
[src:coating/adhesion] This follows from the aforementioned crack failure – the stress at the interface is not uniformly distributed, but rather concentrated at the area of failure.
[src:coating/adhesion] Some conducting materials may pass electrons to form a difference in electrical charge at the joint.
[src:coating/adhesion] This results in a structure similar to a capacitor and creates an attractive electrostatic force between the materials.
[src:coating/adhesion] Some materials may merge at the joint by diffusion.
[src:coating/adhesion] This may occur when the molecules of both materials are mobile and soluble in each other.
[src:coating/adhesion] This would be particularly effective with polymer chains where one end of the molecule diffuses into the other material.
[src:coating/adhesion] It is also the mechanism involved in sintering.
[src:coating/adhesion] When metal or ceramic powders are pressed together and heated, atoms diffuse from one particle to the next.
[src:coating/adhesion] Diffusive forces are somewhat like mechanical tethering at the molecular level.
[src:coating/adhesion] Diffusive bonding occurs when species from one surface penetrate into an adjacent surface while still being bound to the phase of their surface of origin.
[src:coating/adhesion] One instructive example is that of polymer-on-polymer surfaces.
[src:coating/adhesion] Diffusive bonding in polymer-on-polymer surfaces is the result of sections of polymer chains from one surface interdigitating with those of an adjacent surface.
[src:coating/adhesion] The freedom of movement of the polymers has a strong effect on their ability to interdigitate, and hence, on diffusive bonding.
[src:coating/adhesion] For example, cross-linked polymers are less capable of diffusion and interdigitation because they are bonded together at many points of contact, and are not free to twist into the adjacent surface.
[src:coating/adhesion] Uncrosslinked polymers (thermoplastics), on the other hand are freer to wander into the adjacent phase by extending tails and loops across the interface.
[src:coating/adhesion] Another circumstance under which diffusive bonding occurs is "scission".
[src:coating/adhesion] Chain scission is the cutting up of polymer chains, resulting in a higher concentration of distal tails.
[src:coating/adhesion] The heightened concentration of these chain ends gives rise to a heightened concentration of polymer tails extending across the interface.
[src:coating/adhesion] Scission is easily achieved by ultraviolet irradiation in the presence of oxygen gas, which suggests that adhesive devices employing diffusive bonding actually benefit from prolonged exposure to heat/light and air.
[src:coating/adhesion] The longer such a device is exposed to these conditions, the more tails are scissed and branch out across the interface.
[src:coating/adhesion] Once across the interface, the tails and loops form whatever bonds are favorable.
[src:coating/adhesion] In the case of polymer-on-polymer surfaces, this means more van der Waals forces.
[src:coating/adhesion] While these may be brittle, they are quite strong when a large network of these bonds is formed.
[src:coating/adhesion] The outermost layer of each surface plays a crucial role in the adhesive properties of such interfaces, as even a tiny amount of interdigitation – as little as one or two tails of 1.25 angstrom length – can increase the van der Waals bonds by an order of magnitude.
[src:coating/adhesion] The strength of the adhesion between two materials depends on which of the above mechanisms occur between the two materials, and the surface area over which the two materials contact.
[src:coating/adhesion] Materials that wet against each other tend to have a larger contact area than those that do not.
[src:coating/adhesion] Wetting depends on the surface energy of the materials.
[src:coating/adhesion] Low surface energy materials such as polyethylene, polypropylene, polytetrafluoroethylene and polyoxymethylene are difficult to bond without special surface preparation.
[src:coating/adhesion] Another factor determining the strength of an adhesive contact is its shape.
[src:coating/adhesion] Adhesive contacts of complex shape begin to detach at the "edges" of the contact area.
[src:coating/adhesion] The process of destruction of adhesive contacts can be seen in the film.
[src:coating/adhesion] Recent experimental work has shown that adhesion-force measurements often exhibit non-Gaussian variability, and in some cases the normalized force distribution can be accurately represented using a Beta distribution.
[src:coating/adhesion] In concert with the primary surface forces described above, there are several circumstantial effects in play.
[src:coating/adhesion] While the forces themselves each contribute to the magnitude of the adhesion between the surfaces, the following play a crucial role in the overall strength and reliability of an adhesive device.
[src:coating/adhesion] Stringing is perhaps the most crucial of these effects, and is often seen on adhesive tapes.
[src:coating/adhesion] Stringing occurs when a separation of two surfaces is beginning and molecules at the interface bridge out across the gap, rather than cracking like the interface itself.
[src:coating/adhesion] The most significant consequence of this effect is the restraint of the crack.
[src:coating/adhesion] By providing the otherwise brittle interfacial bonds with some flexibility, the molecules that are stringing across the gap can stop the crack from propagating.
[src:coating/adhesion] Another way to understand this phenomenon is by comparing it to the stress concentration at the point of failure mentioned earlier.
[src:coating/adhesion] Since the stress is now spread out over some area, the stress at any given point has less of a chance of overwhelming the total adhesive force between the surfaces.
[src:coating/adhesion] If failure does occur at an interface containing a viscoelastic adhesive agent, and a crack does propagate, it happens by a gradual process called "fingering", rather than a rapid, brittle fracture.
[src:coating/adhesion] Stringing can apply to both the diffusive bonding regime and the chemical bonding regime.
[src:coating/adhesion] The strings of molecules bridging across the gap would either be the molecules that had earlier diffused across the interface or the viscoelastic adhesive, provided that there was a significant volume of it at the interface.
[src:coating/adhesion] The interplay of molecular scale mechanisms and hierarchical surface structures is known to result in high levels of static friction and bonding between pairs of surfaces.
[src:coating/adhesion] Technologically advanced adhesive devices sometimes make use of microstructures on surfaces, such as tightly packed periodic posts.
[src:coating/adhesion] These are biomimetic technologies inspired by the adhesive abilities of the feet of various arthropods and vertebrates (most notably, geckos).
[src:coating/adhesion] By intermixing periodic breaks into smooth, adhesive surfaces, the interface acquires valuable crack-arresting properties.
[src:coating/adhesion] Because crack initiation requires much greater stress than does crack propagation, surfaces like these are much harder to separate, as a new crack has to be restarted every time the next individual microstructure is reached.
[src:coating/adhesion] Hysteresis, in this case, refers to the restructuring of the adhesive interface over some period of time, with the result being that the work needed to separate two surfaces is greater than the work that was gained by bringing them together (W > γ1 + γ2).
[src:coating/adhesion] For the most part, this is a phenomenon associated with diffusive bonding.
[src:coating/adhesion] The more time is given for a pair of surfaces exhibiting diffusive bonding to restructure, the more diffusion will occur, the stronger the adhesion will become.
[src:coating/adhesion] The aforementioned reaction of certain polymer-on-polymer surfaces to ultraviolet radiation and oxygen gas is an instance of hysteresis, but it will also happen over time without those factors.
[src:coating/adhesion] In addition to being able to observe hysteresis by determining if W > γ1 + γ2 is true, one can also find evidence of it by performing "stop-start" measurements.
[src:coating/adhesion] In these experiments, two surfaces slide against one another continuously and occasionally stopped for some measured amount of time.
[src:coating/adhesion] Results from experiments on polymer-on-polymer surfaces show that if the stopping time is short enough, resumption of smooth sliding is easy.
[src:coating/adhesion] If, however, the stopping time exceeds some limit, there is an initial increase of resistance to motion, indicating that the stopping time was sufficient for the surfaces to restructure.
[src:coating/adhesion] Some atmospheric effects on the functionality of adhesive devices can be characterized by following the theory of surface energy and interfacial tension.
[src:coating/adhesion] If γ12 is high, then each species finds it favorable to cohere while in contact with a foreign species, rather than dissociate and mix with the other.
[src:coating/adhesion] If this is true, then it follows that when the interfacial tension is high, the force of adhesion is weak, since each species does not find it favorable to bond to the other.
[src:coating/adhesion] The interfacial tension of a liquid and a solid is directly related to the liquid's wettability (relative to the solid), and thus one can extrapolate that cohesion increases in non-wetting liquids and decreases in wetting liquids.
[src:coating/adhesion] One example that verifies this is polydimethyl siloxane rubber, which has a work of self-adhesion of 43.6 mJ/m2 in air, 74 mJ/m2 in water (a nonwetting liquid) and 6 mJ/m2 in methanol (a wetting liquid).
[src:coating/adhesion] This argument can be extended to the idea that when a surface is in a medium with which binding is favorable, it will be less likely to adhere to another surface, since the medium is taking up the potential sites on the surface that would otherwise be available to adhere to another surface.
[src:coating/adhesion] Naturally this applies very strongly to wetting liquids, but also to gas molecules that could adsorb onto the surface in question, thereby occupying potential adhesion sites.
[src:coating/adhesion] This last point is actually fairly intuitive: Leaving an adhesive exposed to air too long gets it dirty, and its adhesive strength will decrease.
[src:coating/adhesion] This is observed in the experiment: when mica is cleaved in air, its cleavage energy, W121 or Wmica/air/mica, is smaller than the cleavage energy in vacuum, Wmica/vac/mica, by a factor of 13.
[src:coating/adhesion] Lateral adhesion is associated with sliding one object on a substrate, such as sliding a drop on a surface.
[src:coating/adhesion] When the two objects are solids, either with or without a liquid between them, the lateral adhesion is described as *friction*.
[src:coating/adhesion] However, the behavior of lateral adhesion between a drop and a surface is tribologically very different from friction between solids, and the naturally adhesive contact between a flat surface and a liquid drop makes the lateral adhesion in this case, an individual field.
[src:coating/adhesion] Lateral adhesion can be measured using the centrifugal adhesion balance (CAB), which uses a combination of centrifugal and gravitational forces to decouple the normal and lateral forces in the problem.
[src:coating/air-knife] An **air knife** is a tool used to blow off liquid or debris from products as they travel on conveyors.
[src:coating/air-knife] Air knives are normally used in manufacturing or as the first step in a recursive recycling process to separate lighter or smaller particles from other components for use in later or subsequent steps, post manufacturing parts drying and conveyor cleaning, part of component cleaning.
[src:coating/air-knife] The knife consists of a high-intensity, uniform sheet of laminar airflow sometimes known as streamline flow.
[src:coating/air-knife] An industrial air knife is a pressurized air plenum containing a series of holes or continuous slots through which pressurized air exits in a laminar flow pattern.
[src:coating/air-knife] The exit air velocity then creates an impact air velocity onto the surface of whatever object the air is directed.
[src:coating/air-knife] This impact air velocity can range from a gentle breeze to greater than Mach 0.6 (40,000 ft/min) to alter the surface of a product without mechanical contact.
[src:coating/air-knife] Air knives remove liquids, control the thickness of liquids, dry the liquid coatings, remove foreign particles, cool product surfaces or create a hold down force to assist in the mechanical bonding of materials to the surface.
[src:coating/air-knife] Electrical currents from anti-static bars can also be injected into the exit air knife stream to neutralize the static electricity charge on some surfaces.
[src:coating/air-knife] In the majority of manufacturing applications for air knives, the air knives are stationary while the product passes through the air velocity air stream.
[src:coating/air-knife] In other circumstances, the product is stationary and the air knives move (reciprocate or rotate) over the surface of the stationary product.
[src:coating/air-knife] Although there are very few applications where an air knife can actually cut a product (break mechanical bonds between two points), air knives are often the most efficient method of removing or controlling unwanted or foreign substances on any surface.
[src:coating/air-knife] In reference to the galvanizing industry, air knives are used to precisely control the amount of zinc coating by wiping away the coating while it is still in a liquid state on the steel surface.
[src:coating/air-knife] In most hot dip applications both top and bottom coated surfaces can be independently controlled by computer via feedback loop as accurately as plus or minus 5 grams/meter squared.
[src:coating/air-knife] Most air knife systems for this application use heated nitrogen gas as the wiping agent, not atmospheric air.
[src:coating/air-knife] Nitrogen is used to reduce oxidation of the base metal.
[src:coating/air-knife] In the 1950s and 60s, the term "**air doctor**" was first used to refer to the non-contact method of debris blow-off using compressed air.
[src:coating/air-knife] The printing and textile industries were some of the largest users of air doctors at that time, named by analogy with "doctor rolls" and "doctor blades".
[src:coating/air-knife] They often needed wide paths of air from a compressed air system to control the thickness of liquids on a surface, or to blow debris off the surface of materials prior to the next process.
[src:coating/air-knife] Other terms used were air bar, air squeegee, air curtain, air jet, air blast, air blow off, air nozzle, air comb, air blade and air doctor blade.
[src:coating/air-knife] Today the most commonly used term is simply "air knife".
[src:coating/air-knife] Although air knives powered by compressed plant air are used in a wide variety of industrial applications, industrial blower-powered air knives have proven to reduce the energy usage versus compressed air knives by 50–75% for most applications.
[src:coating/air-knife] Blower-powered air knife systems came of age with the advent of the 1987 Montreal Protocol, which started the clock on the worldwide phase-out of atmospheric ozone depleting CFC’s (chlorofluorocarbons) then used as cleaning agents in many industries.
[src:coating/air-knife] Most of these solvent-based cleaning agents simply evaporated which required no blow-off or other drying methods.
[src:coating/air-knife] Although the printed circuit board industry was still in its infancy, it was among the first to initiate the conversion to aqueous and semi-aqueous-based parts cleaning systems.
[src:coating/air-knife] With nearly every existing and all future circuit board factories using the new environmentally friendly cleaning technology, they also needed a new method of drying the p.c. boards following their water-based cleaning to remove solder fluxes and other contaminants.
[src:coating/air-knife] The trend away from other types of solvent-based parts cleaning to water-based cleaning for other industries began soon thereafter.
[src:coating/air-knife] Additionally, the conversion to water-based inks, paints, coatings, adhesives and other solutions used in various manufacturing sectors has resulted in the need for air knife dryers where none had previously existed.
[src:coating/air-knife] As a result of the Montreal Protocol and worldwide industry compliance with environmental stewardship mandates, the former niche business of air knives became an industry.
[src:coating/air-knife] Air knives on a production line commonly range from 0.25 to 200 inches (6.4 to 5,080.0 mm) in length with a discharge air slot or holes ranging from 0.001 to 0.25 in (0.025 to 6.350 mm).
[src:coating/air-knife] A stationary air knife configuration can require from one to a dozen air knives depending on the application criteria.
[src:coating/air-knife] Air is blasted through the air knife slots via an air generator, either an industrial blower or air compressor, to deliver the predetermined exit air volume and velocity needed.
[src:coating/air-knife] There are many application, environmental, efficiency and duty cycle aspects to consider when choosing between compressors and blowers.
[src:coating/air-knife] Compressed air, which is least efficient when used for air knives discharging into free air, allows for use of primary plant air.
[src:coating/air-knife] The piping sizes supplying the air knives can be as little as 1⁄4 in (6.4 mm) diameter, so they are ideal for confined spaces.
[src:coating/air-knife] Blower-powered air knives must be larger in size along with larger diameter supply piping, but the efficiency improvement over compressed air is easily justified with the electrical power cost savings.
[src:coating/air-knife] Air knife designs today have evolved to where some manufacturers produce a very efficient “teardrop” shape with a .95 coefficient of discharge.
[src:coating/air-knife] With construction ranging from 1⁄8 in (3.2 mm) thick aluminum extrusion to 11 gauge fabricated stainless steel, air knives can weigh 1 lb/ft to 25 lbs/ft.
[src:coating/air-knife] Depending on the width and speed of the product, the air knife can provide effective blow-off performance from 0.5 to 12 in (13 to 305 mm) or more away from the surface of the product.
[src:coating/air-knife] Round air nozzles of 1 to 4 in (25 to 102 mm) diameter can be effective against surfaces which are up to several feet (1 to 2 meters) from the product surface when engineered for such applications.
[src:coating/air-knife] The most common use of air knives is to contain or remove free-standing materials (liquids or solids) from the surface of material.
[src:coating/air-knife] The applications include drying bottles and cans after filling and rinsing, printed circuit boards following the conveyorized wash to remove solder paste and flux, metals castings after automatic machining and many more.
[src:coating/air-knife] There is a variety of uses for air knives in many different industries, applications and environments.
[src:coating/air-knife] The invisible-high velocity air streams can be discharged by air knife designs of numerous shapes and sizes.
[src:coating/air-knife] These range from “garage built” devices with a low level of precision to the most exotic metals of construction used in air knives for class 100 clean rooms.
[src:coating/air-knife] In instances where noise reduction and moisture containment around a conveyorized air knife installation becomes important, some manufacturing facilities have installed air knives within an enclosure.
[src:coating/air-knife] These enclosures keep water contained, reduce the amount of air knife noise and even eliminate any liquid that could create safety concerns.
[src:coating/air-knife] There has always been a wide assortment of blow-off appliances.
[src:coating/air-knife] Air knives and nozzles for compressed air blow-off range from home made round pipes with holes to engineered high pressure air knives.
[src:coating/air-knife] In order to achieve the highest efficiency using compressed air, many manufacturers of compressed air knives utilize the Coandă effect to improve compressed air knife design over other types of knives and nozzles.
[src:coating/air-knife] Although the efficiency of compressed air for low-pressure blow-off air is much lower than blowers, the Coanda-inspired air knives entrain ambient air into the high-velocity stream to enhance the blow off effect.
[src:coating/air-knife] The teardrop-shaped air knife has a bulbous plenum which tapers down to a precise air discharge slot as the standard of the blower driven air knife industry.
[src:coating/air-knife] These teardrop designs are available in extruded aluminum shapes as well as fabricated carbon and stainless steels.
[src:coating/anilox] In printing, **anilox** is a method used to provide a measured amount of ink to a flexographic (flexo) printing plate.
[src:coating/anilox] An **anilox roll** is a hard cylinder, usually constructed of a steel or aluminum core which is coated by an industrial ceramic, typically chromium(III) oxide powder, whose surface is engraved with millions of very fine dimples, known as anilox cells.
[src:coating/anilox] In the printing process, the anilox roll is coated in a precise layer of ink that is then transferred to the raised portions of the printing plate.
[src:coating/anilox] The number, size, and geometry of the anilox cells vary and will determine the amount of ink that the anilox roll delivers to the plate.
[src:coating/anilox] Depending on the detail of the images to be printed, the press operator will select an anilox roll with a higher or lower line screen.
[src:coating/anilox] "Line screen" is the term used for the number of cells engraved on the anilox.
[src:coating/anilox] Low line screen rolls (100-300 lpi) are used where a heavy layer of ink is desired, such as in heavy block lettering.
[src:coating/anilox] Higher line screens (500-1500 lpi) produce finer details and are used in four-color process work such as reproducing photographs.
[src:coating/anilox] Often a job will require a different line screen for each color to be printed.
[src:coating/anilox] Experienced press operators are skilled at determining the appropriate rolls for a given print job.
[src:coating/anilox] Depending on the design of the printing press, the anilox roll is either semi-submerged in the ink fountain, or comes into contact with a so-called metering roller, which is semi-submerged in the ink fountain.
[src:coating/anilox] In either instance, a thick layer of typically viscous ink is deposited on the roller.
[src:coating/anilox] A doctor blade is used to shave excess ink from the surface leaving just the measured amount of ink in the cells.
[src:coating/anilox] The roll then rotates to make contact with the flexographic printing plate which receives the ink from the cells for transfer to the printed material.
[src:coating/anilox] Anilox roll selection should be based on cell volume or capacity of the engraved cells.
[src:coating/anilox] Print results are accomplished with this volume, which transfers to the printing plate and then to the substrate.
[src:coating/anilox] In general transfer, efficiency is approximately 25% to the substrate.
[src:coating/anilox] Cell count remains the same for the life of the roll, while volume changes over time due to wear, plugging and damage.
[src:coating/anilox] Cell count accommodates volume at various cell shapes available from the laser engraving process.
[src:coating/anilox] The same cell count can be engraved to or wear to different volumes.
[src:coating/anilox] Contemporary ink metering systems employ a self contained system known as a chambered doctor blade system which is basically a manifold which delivers ink to the anilox roll.
[src:coating/anilox] Ink is pumped through a hose to the chamber which fills to capacity.
[src:coating/anilox] Ink is retained within the system by end seals and doctor blades.
[src:coating/anilox] One blade works as a retaining blade, simply holding ink within the chamber.
[src:coating/anilox] The other reverse angle blade works as previously described, removing excess ink from the engraved surface of the anilox roll.
[src:coating/anilox] Chambered doctor blade systems are recognized for high quality, consistency and accuracy removing the influence of press speed and some human subjectivity.
[src:coating/anilox] Anilox rolls were originally made using a process of mechanical engraving, utilizing hardened steel tools of various cell counts and cell shapes diamond pecking machine, but modern rolls are laser engraved.
[src:coating/anilox] The characteristics of an anilox roll determine the amount of ink that will be transferred to the plate: angle of the cells, cell volume, and line screen.
[src:coating/anilox] A 60 degree angle ensures maximum density in a given space.
[src:coating/anilox] Low line numbers will allow for a heavy layer of ink to be printed, whereas high line numbers will permit finer detail in printing.
[src:coating/anilox] Both cell volume and line screen are closely correlated.
[src:coating/anilox] The rolls are often specified by their line screen, which is the number of cells per linear inch.
[src:coating/anilox] These often range from around 250 to upwards of 2000, though the precise numbers vary by manufacturer.
[src:coating/anilox] Most rolls sold are within 800 LPI, although a spike in demand for those with 800–1200 lines has been seen.
[src:coating/anilox] Anilox rolls are almost always designed to be removed from the press for cleaning and for swapping out with different line screen rolls.
[src:coating/anilox] Anilox rolls are properly specified by cell volume for the required print application.
[src:coating/anilox] Lower volumes = thinner ink films for the highest quality process printing.
[src:coating/anilox] Higher volumes address combination, screens, line work, solid coverage and coating applications.
[src:coating/anilox] In virtually all printing applications with various print requirements, one volume will not print all to the highest quality.
[src:coating/anilox] Limited print stations generally call for a compromise between the highest quality graphics and color.
[src:coating/anilox] There are many variables to consider when specifying an anilox roll beyond the print requirements, such as substrate, ink system, plate material, plate mounting tape, press speed, and drying capacity.
[src:coating/anilox] The best course of action is to consult suppliers of all these components for proper engraving specifications from their experience.
[src:coating/anilox] There are two ways to specify anilox roll settings: on transfer volume or on line count.
[src:coating/anilox] Each specification has both a European standard and an American standard.
[src:coating/anilox] Transfer volume is the volume of ink that will be transferred per unit surface area of paper.
[src:coating/anilox] The European standard for transfer volume is cm3/m2 or cubic centimetre per square meter, which means 1 cm3 of ink will be transferred onto 1 m2 of paper.
[src:coating/anilox] Sometimes ink suppliers will give a recommended transfer weight per square meter, expressed in g/m2.
[src:coating/anilox] This can be converted to cm3/m2 by dividing by the density of the ink in g/cm3.
[src:coating/anilox] The American standard for transfer volume is a billion cubic microns per square inch, typically written as BCM / in2, BCM/sq in, or BCM.
[src:coating/anilox] A cubic micron (μm3) is a unit of volume and one billion cubic microns (1 000 000 000 μm3) is equal to 0.001 cm3.
[src:coating/anilox] Since one square meter is equal to 1550 square inches, it follows that 1 BCM/in2 = 1.55 cm3/m2.
[src:coating/anilox] Line count measures the fineness of the pattern on the anilox roll.
[src:coating/anilox] It measures how many cells are engraved per centimetre or inch.
[src:coating/anilox] In Europe the standard is LPCM or lines per centimeter.
[src:coating/anilox] In America, the standard is LPI or lines per inch.
[src:coating/anilox] The conversion from transfer volume to line count is not straightforward.
[src:coating/anilox] This is because depending on the pattern used for the cell and depth of gravure of the anilox roll, the cell might contain higher or lower volumes of ink.
[src:coating/anilox] The only way to convert cm3/m2 (transfer volume) to LPCM (cell finesse) or BCM to LPI is to look at the conversion chart provided by the anilox roll supplier.
[src:coating/anilox] Also, any given anilox roll will age after some time and its actual transfer volume will be less and less.
[src:coating/anilox] Though large wide-web flexo rolls are only maneuverable by overhead crane, on smaller presses anilox rolls are often handled directly by operators.
[src:coating/anilox] Extreme caution must be taken when handling these pieces of hardware as a single bump against a hard surface or sharp corner can destroy the delicate cell structure on the surface and render a roller completely useless, at a cost of around US$5000 for even small narrow-web rollers.
[src:coating/anilox] Nicks and scratches add up quickly, so fine brushes (never brass brushes) are used for cleaning the anilox roll.
[src:coating/anilox] Anilox rollers that are used with water, solvent and oil based inks, which dry when left sitting out and unagitated, must be cleaned immediately after use or a problem known as plugging occurs, where minuscule amounts of ink dry in the cells.
[src:coating/anilox] This leaves tiny, but unacceptable, pinholes in anything printed from the roll in the future.
[src:coating/anilox] Anilox rolls can also become damaged if a steel doctor blade breaks and begins to grind the anilox roll.
[src:coating/anilox] This creates a defect in the print called a "score line" due to the scoring of the anilox.
[src:coating/anilox] Ceramic Anilox are routinely manufactured by plasma spraying chromium(III) oxide powders (Cr2O3) on to the roller or sleeve surface.
[src:coating/anilox] Chromium oxide is manufactured by calcining sodium dichromate in the presence of carbon or sulfur.
[src:coating/anodising] The process is called *anodizing* because the part to be treated forms the anode electrode of an electrolytic cell.
[src:coating/anodising] Anodizing increases resistance to corrosion and wear, and provides better adhesion for paint primers and glues than bare metal does.
[src:coating/anodising] Anodic films can also be used for several cosmetic effects, either with thick porous coatings that can absorb dyes or with thin coatings whose color is due to thin film interference.
[src:coating/anodising] Anodizing is also used to prevent galling of threaded components and to make dielectric films for electrolytic capacitors.
[src:coating/anodising] Anodic films are most commonly applied to protect aluminium alloys, although processes also exist for titanium, zinc, magnesium, niobium, zirconium, hafnium, and tantalum.
[src:coating/anodising] Carbon flakes or nodules in iron or steel with high carbon content (high-carbon steel, cast iron) may cause an electrolytic potential and interfere with coating or plating.
[src:coating/anodising] Ferrous metals are commonly anodized electrolytically in nitric acid or by treatment with red fuming nitric acid to form hard black Iron(II,III) oxide.
[src:coating/anodising] This oxide remains conformal even when plated on wiring and the wiring is bent.
[src:coating/anodising] Anodizing changes the microscopic texture of the surface and the crystal structure of the metal near the surface.
[src:coating/anodising] Thick coatings are normally porous, so a sealing process is often needed to achieve corrosion resistance.
[src:coating/anodising] Anodized aluminium surfaces, for example, are harder than aluminium but have low to moderate wear resistance that can be improved with increasing thickness or by applying suitable sealing substances.
[src:coating/anodising] Anodic films are generally much stronger and more adherent than most types of paint and metal plating, but also more brittle.
[src:coating/anodising] This makes them less likely to crack and peel from ageing and wear, but more susceptible to cracking from thermal stress.
[src:coating/anodising] Anodizing was first used on an industrial scale in 1923 to protect Duralumin seaplane parts from corrosion.
[src:coating/anodising] This early chromic acid–based process was called the Bengough–Stuart process and was documented in British defence specification DEF STAN 03-24/3.
[src:coating/anodising] It is still used today despite its legacy requirements for a complicated voltage cycle now known to be unnecessary.
[src:coating/anodising] Variations of this process soon evolved, and the first sulfuric acid anodizing process was patented by Gower and O'Brien in 1927.
[src:coating/anodising] Sulfuric acid soon became and remains the most common anodizing electrolyte.
[src:coating/anodising] Oxalic acid anodizing was first patented in Japan in 1923 and later widely used in Germany, particularly for architectural applications.
[src:coating/anodising] Anodized aluminium extrusion was a popular architectural material in the 1960s and 1970s, but has since been displaced by cheaper plastics and powder coating.
[src:coating/anodising] The phosphoric acid processes are the most recent major development, so far only used as pretreatments for adhesives or organic paints.
[src:coating/anodising] A wide variety of proprietary and increasingly complex variations of all these anodizing processes continue to be developed by industry, so the growing trend in military and industrial standards is to classify by coating properties rather than by process chemistry.
[src:coating/anodising] Aluminium alloys are anodized to increase corrosion resistance and to allow dyeing (coloring), improved lubrication, or improved adhesion.
[src:coating/anodising] However, anodizing does not increase the strength of the aluminium object.
[src:coating/anodising] When exposed to air at room temperature, or any other gas containing oxygen, pure aluminium self-passivates by forming a surface layer of amorphous aluminium oxide 2 to 3 nm thick, which provides very effective protection against corrosion.
[src:coating/anodising] Aluminium alloys typically form a thicker oxide layer, 5–15 nm thick, but tend to be more susceptible to corrosion.
[src:coating/anodising] Aluminium alloy parts are anodized to greatly increase the thickness of this layer for corrosion resistance.
[src:coating/anodising] The corrosion resistance of aluminium alloys is significantly decreased by certain alloying elements or impurities: copper, iron, and silicon, so 2000-, 4000-, 6000 and 7000-series Al alloys tend to be most susceptible.
[src:coating/anodising] Although anodizing produces a very regular and uniform coating, microscopic fissures in the coating can lead to corrosion.
[src:coating/anodising] Further, the coating is susceptible to chemical dissolution in the presence of high- and low-pH chemistry, which results in stripping the coating and corrosion of the substrate.
[src:coating/anodising] To combat this, various techniques have been developed either to reduce the number of fissures, to insert more chemically stable compounds into the oxide, or both.
[src:coating/anodising] For instance, sulphuric-anodized articles are normally sealed, either through hydro-thermal sealing or precipitating sealing, to reduce porosity and interstitial pathways that allow corrosive ion exchange between the surface and the substrate.
[src:coating/anodising] Precipitating seals enhance chemical stability but are less effective in eliminating ionic exchange pathways.
[src:coating/anodising] Most recently, new techniques to partially convert the amorphous oxide coating into more stable micro-crystalline compounds have been developed that have shown significant improvement based on shorter bond lengths.
[src:coating/anodising] Some aluminium aircraft parts, architectural materials, and consumer products are anodized.
[src:coating/anodising] Anodized aluminium can be found on MP3 players, smartphones, multi-tools, flashlights, cookware, cameras, sporting goods, firearms, window frames, roofs, in electrolytic capacitors, and on many other products both for corrosion resistance and the ability to retain dye.
[src:coating/anodising] Although anodizing only has moderate wear resistance, the deeper pores can better retain a lubricating film than a smooth surface would.
[src:coating/anodising] Anodized coatings have a much lower thermal conductivity and coefficient of linear expansion than aluminium.
[src:coating/anodising] As a result, the coating will crack from thermal stress if exposed to temperatures above 80 °C (353 K).
[src:coating/anodising] The coating can crack, but it will not peel.
[src:coating/anodising] The melting point of aluminium oxide is 2050 °C (2323K), much higher than pure aluminium's 658 °C (931K).
[src:coating/anodising] This and the insulativity of aluminium oxide can make welding more difficult.
[src:coating/anodising] In typical commercial aluminium anodizing processes, the aluminium oxide is grown down into the surface and out from the surface by equal amounts.
[src:coating/anodising] Therefore, anodizing will increase the part dimensions on each surface by half the oxide thickness.
[src:coating/anodising] For example, a coating that is 2 μm thick will increase the part dimensions by 1 μm per surface.
[src:coating/anodising] If the part is anodized on all sides, then all linear dimensions will increase by the oxide thickness.
[src:coating/anodising] Anodized aluminium surfaces are harder than aluminium but have low to moderate wear resistance, although this can be improved with thickness and sealing.
[src:coating/anodising] A desmut solution can be applied to the surface of aluminium to remove contaminants.
[src:coating/anodising] Nitric acid is typically used to remove smut (residue), but is being replaced because of environmental concerns.
[src:coating/anodising] The anodized aluminium layer is created by passing a direct current through an electrolytic solution, with the aluminium object serving as the anode (the positive electrode in an electrolytic cell).
[src:coating/anodising] The current releases hydrogen at the cathode (the negative electrode) and oxygen at the surface of the aluminium anode, creating a build-up of aluminium oxide.
[src:coating/anodising] Alternating current and pulsed current is also possible but rarely used.
[src:coating/anodising] The voltage required by various solutions may range from 1 to 300 V DC, although most fall in the range of 15 to 21 V.
[src:coating/anodising] Higher voltages are typically required for thicker coatings formed in sulfuric and organic acid.
[src:coating/anodising] The anodizing current varies with the area of aluminium being anodized and typically ranges from 30 to 300 A/m2.
[src:coating/anodising] Aluminium anodizing (eloxal or **El**ectrolytic **Ox**idation of **Al**uminium) is usually performed in an acidic solution, typically sulphuric acid or chromic acid, which slowly dissolves the aluminium oxide.
[src:coating/anodising] The acid action is balanced with the oxidation rate to form a coating with nanopores, 10–150 nm in diameter.
[src:coating/anodising] These pores are what allow the electrolyte solution and current to reach the aluminium substrate and continue growing the coating to greater thickness beyond what is produced by auto-passivation.
[src:coating/anodising] These pores allow for the dye to be absorbed, however, this must be followed by sealing or the dye will not stay.
[src:coating/anodising] Dye is typically followed up by a clean nickel acetate seal.
[src:coating/anodising] Because the dye is only superficial, the underlying oxide may continue to provide corrosion protection even if minor wear and scratches break through the dyed layer.
[src:coating/anodising] Conditions such as electrolyte concentration, acidity, solution temperature, and current must be controlled to allow the formation of a consistent oxide layer.
[src:coating/anodising] Harder, thicker films tend to be produced by more concentrated solutions at lower temperatures with higher voltages and currents.
[src:coating/anodising] The film thickness can range from under 0.5 micrometers for bright decorative work up to 150 micrometers for architectural applications.
[src:coating/anodising] Anodizing can be performed in combination with chromate conversion coating.
[src:coating/anodising] Each process provides corrosion resistance, with anodizing offering a significant advantage when it comes to ruggedness or physical wear resistance.
[src:coating/anodising] The reason for combining the processes can vary, however, the significant difference between anodizing and chromate conversion coating is the electrical conductivity of the films produced.
[src:coating/anodising] Although both stable compounds, chromate conversion coating has a greatly increased electrical conductivity.
[src:coating/anodising] Applications where this may be useful are varied, however the issue of grounding components as part of a larger system is an obvious one.
[src:coating/anodising] The dual finishing process uses the best each process has to offer, anodizing with its hard wear resistance and chromate conversion coating with its electrical conductivity.
[src:coating/anodising] The process steps can typically involve chromate conversion coating the entire component, followed by a masking of the surface in areas where the chromate coating must remain intact.
[src:coating/anodising] Beyond that, the chromate coating is then dissolved in unmasked areas.
[src:coating/anodising] The component can then be anodized, with anodizing taking to the unmasked areas.
[src:coating/anodising] The exact process will vary dependent on service provider, component geometry and required outcome.
[src:coating/anodising] The most widely used anodizing specification in the US is a U.S. military spec, MIL-A-8625, which defines three types of aluminium anodizing.
[src:coating/anodising] Type I is chromic acid anodizing, Type II is sulphuric acid anodizing, and Type III is sulphuric acid hard anodizing.
[src:coating/anodising] None of these specifications define a detailed process or chemistry, but rather a set of tests and quality assurance measures which the anodized product must meet.
[src:coating/anodising] BS 1615 guides the selection of alloys for anodizing.
[src:coating/anodising] For British defense work, a detailed chromic and sulfuric anodizing processes are described by DEF STAN 03-24/3 and DEF STAN 03-25/3 respectively.
[src:coating/anodising] The oldest anodizing process uses chromic acid.
[src:coating/anodising] It is widely known as the Bengough-Stuart process but, due to the safety regulations regarding air quality control, is not preferred by vendors when the additive material associated with type II doesn't break tolerances.
[src:coating/anodising] In North America, it is known as Type I because it is so designated by the MIL-A-8625 standard, but it is also covered by AMS 2470 and MIL-A-8625 Type IB.
[src:coating/anodising] In the UK it is normally specified as Def Stan 03/24 and used in areas that are prone to come into contact with propellants etc.
[src:coating/anodising] There are also Boeing and Airbus standards.
[src:coating/anodising] Chromic acid produces thinner, 0.5 μm to 18 μm (0.00002" to 0.0007") more opaque films that are softer, ductile, and to a degree self-healing.
[src:coating/anodising] They are harder to dye and may be applied as a pretreatment before painting.
[src:coating/anodising] The method of film formation is different from using sulfuric acid in that the voltage is ramped up through the process cycle.
[src:coating/anodising] Sulfuric acid is the most widely used solution to produce an anodized coating.
[src:coating/anodising] Coatings of moderate thickness 1.8 μm to 25 μm (0.00007" to 0.001") are known as Type II in North America, as named by MIL-A-8625, while coatings thicker than 25 μm (0.001") are known as Type III, hard-coat, hard anodizing, or engineered anodizing.
[src:coating/anodising] Very thin coatings similar to those produced by chromic anodizing are known as Type IIB.
[src:coating/anodising] Thick coatings require more process control, and are produced in a refrigerated tank near the freezing point of water with higher voltages than the thinner coatings.
[src:coating/anodising] Hard anodizing can be made between 13 and 150 μm (0.0005" to 0.006") thick.
[src:coating/anodising] Anodizing thickness increases wear resistance, corrosion resistance, ability to retain lubricants and PTFE coatings, and electrical and thermal insulation.
[src:coating/anodising] Sealing Type III will improve corrosion resistance at the cost of reducing abrasion resistance.
[src:coating/anodising] Standards for thin (Soft/Standard) sulfuric anodizing are given by MIL-A-8625 Types II and IIB, AMS 2471 (undyed), and AMS 2472 (dyed), BS EN ISO 12373/1 (decorative), BS 3987 (Architectural).
[src:coating/anodising] Standards for thick sulphuric anodizing are given by MIL-A-8625 Type III, AMS 2469, BS ISO 10074, BS EN 2536 and the obsolete AMS 2468 and DEF STAN 03-26/1.
[src:coating/anodising] Anodizing can produce yellowish integral colors without dyes if it is carried out in weak acids with high voltages, high current densities, and strong refrigeration.
[src:coating/anodising] Shades of color are restricted to a range which includes pale yellow, gold, deep bronze, brown, grey, and black.
[src:coating/anodising] Some advanced variations can produce a white coating with 80% reflectivity.
[src:coating/anodising] The shade of color produced is sensitive to variations in the metallurgy of the underlying alloy and cannot be reproduced consistently.
[src:coating/anodising] Anodizing in some organic acids, for example malic acid, can enter a 'runaway' situation, in which the current drives the acid to attack the aluminium far more aggressively than normal, resulting in huge pits and scarring.
[src:coating/anodising] Also, if the current or voltage are driven too high, 'burning' can set in; in this case, the supplies act as if nearly shorted and large, uneven and amorphous black regions develop.
[src:coating/anodising] Integral color anodizing is generally done with organic acids, but the same effect has been produced in laboratories with very dilute sulfuric acid.
[src:coating/anodising] Integral color anodizing was originally performed with oxalic acid, but sulfonated aromatic compounds containing oxygen, particularly sulfosalicylic acid, have been more common since the 1960s.
[src:coating/anodising] Thicknesses of up to 50 μm can be achieved.
[src:coating/anodising] Organic acid anodizing is called Type IC by MIL-A-8625.
[src:coating/anodising] Anodizing can be carried out in phosphoric acid, usually as a surface preparation for adhesives.
[src:coating/anodising] This is described in standard ASTM D3933.
[src:coating/anodising] Anodizing can also be performed in borate or tartrate baths in which aluminium oxide is insoluble.
[src:coating/anodising] In these processes, the coating growth stops when the part is fully covered, and the thickness is linearly related to the voltage applied.
[src:coating/anodising] These coatings are free of pores, relative to the sulfuric and chromic acid processes.
[src:coating/anodising] This type of coating is widely used to make electrolytic capacitors because the thin aluminium films (typically less than 0.5 μm) would risk being pierced by acidic processes.
[src:coating/anodising] Plasma electrolytic oxidation is a similar process, but where higher voltages are applied.
[src:coating/anodising] This causes sparks to occur and results in more crystalline/ceramic type coatings.
[src:coating/anodising] Magnesium is anodized primarily as a primer for paint.
[src:coating/anodising] A thin (5 μm) film is sufficient for this.
[src:coating/anodising] Thicker coatings of 25 μm and up can provide mild corrosion resistance when sealed with oil, wax, or sodium silicate.
[src:coating/anodising] Standards for magnesium anodizing are given in AMS 2466, AMS 2478, AMS 2479, and ASTM B893.
[src:coating/anodising] Niobium anodizes in a similar fashion to titanium with a range of attractive colors being formed by interference at different film thicknesses.
[src:coating/anodising] Again the film thickness is dependent on the anodizing voltage.
[src:coating/anodising] Uses include jewelry and commemorative coins.
[src:coating/anodising] Stainless steel can be anodized in baths containing sulphuric acid and hexavalent chromium compounds.
[src:coating/anodising] Tantalum anodizes similarly to titanium and niobium with a range of attractive colors being formed by interference at different film thicknesses.
[src:coating/anodising] Again the film thickness is dependent on the anodizing voltage and typically ranges from 18 to 23 Angstroms per volt depending on electrolyte and temperature.
[src:coating/anodising] An anodized oxide layer has a thickness in the range of 30 nanometers (1.2×10−6 in) to several micrometers.
[src:coating/anodising] Standards for titanium anodizing are given by AMS 2487 and AMS 2488.
[src:coating/anodising] AMS 2488 Type III anodizing of titanium generates an array of different colors without dyes, for which it is sometimes used in art, costume jewellery, body piercing jewellery and wedding rings.
[src:coating/anodising] The color formed is dependent on the thickness of the oxide (which is determined by the anodizing voltage); it is caused by the interference of light reflecting off the oxide surface with light travelling through it and reflecting off the underlying metal surface.
[src:coating/anodising] AMS 2488 Type II anodizing produces a thicker matte grey finish with higher wear resistance.
[src:coating/anodising] Zinc is rarely anodized, but a process was developed by the International Lead Zinc Research Organization and covered by MIL-A-81801.
[src:coating/anodising] A solution of ammonium phosphate, chromate and fluoride with voltages of up to 200 V can produce olive green coatings up to 80 μm thick.
[src:coating/anodising] The coatings are hard and corrosion resistant.
[src:coating/anodising] Zinc or galvanized steel can be anodized using DC at lower voltages (20–30 V) in silicate baths containing varying concentrations of sodium silicate, sodium hydroxide, borax, sodium nitrite, and nickel sulfate.
[src:coating/anodising] The most common anodizing processes, for example, sulphuric acid on aluminium, produce a porous surface which can accept dyes easily.
[src:coating/anodising] The number of dye colors is almost endless; however, the colors produced tend to vary according to the base alloy.
[src:coating/anodising] The most common colors in the industry, due to them being relatively cheap, are yellow, green, blue, black, orange, purple and red.
[src:coating/anodising] Though some may prefer lighter colors, in practice, they may be difficult to produce on certain alloys such as high-silicon casting grades and 2000-series aluminium-copper alloys.
[src:coating/anodising] Another concern is the "lightfastness" of organic dyestuffs—some colors (reds and blues) are particularly prone to fading.
[src:coating/anodising] Black dyes and gold produced by inorganic means (ferric ammonium oxalate) are more lightfast.
[src:coating/anodising] Dyed anodizing is usually sealed to reduce or eliminate dye bleedout.
[src:coating/anodising] White color cannot be applied due to the larger molecule size than the pore size of the oxide layer.
[src:coating/anodising] Another interesting coloring method is anodizing interference coloring.
[src:coating/anodising] The thin oil film resting on the water's surface displays a rainbow hue due to the interference between light reflected from the water-oil interface and the oil film's surface.
[src:coating/anodising] Because the oil film's thickness isn't regulated, the resulting rainbow color appears random.
[src:coating/anodising] In the anodizing coloring of aluminum, desired colors are achieved by depositing a controllably thick metal layer (typically tin) at the base of the porous structure.
[src:coating/anodising] This involves reflections on the aluminum substrate and the upper metal surface.
[src:coating/anodising] The color resulting from interference shifts from blue, green, and yellow to red as the deposited metal layer thickens.
[src:coating/anodising] Beyond a specific thickness, the optical interference vanishes, and the color turns bronze.
[src:coating/anodising] Interference-colored anodized aluminum parts exhibit a distinctive quality: their color varies when viewed from different angles.
[src:coating/anodising] The interference coloring involves a 3-step process: sulfuric acid anodizing, electrochemical modification of the anodic pore, and metal (tin) deposition.
[src:coating/anodising] Sealing is the final step in the anodizing process.
[src:coating/anodising] Acidic anodizing solutions produce pores in the anodized coating.
[src:coating/anodising] These pores can absorb dyes and retain lubricants, but are also an avenue for corrosion.
[src:coating/anodising] When lubrication properties are not critical, they are usually sealed after dyeing to increase corrosion resistance and dye retention.
[src:coating/anodising] There are three most common types of sealing.
[src:coating/anodising] Mid-temperature sealing process which works at 160–180 °F (70–80 °C) in solutions containing organic additives and metal salts.
[src:coating/anodising] However, this process will likely leach the colors.
[src:coating/anodising] Cold sealing process, where the pores are closed by impregnation of a sealant in a room-temperature bath, is more popular due to energy savings.
[src:coating/anodising] Coatings sealed in this method are not suitable for adhesive bonding.
[src:coating/anodising] Teflon, nickel acetate, cobalt acetate, and hot sodium or potassium dichromate seals are commonly used.
[src:coating/anodising] MIL-A-8625 requires sealing for thin coatings (Types I and II) and allows it as an option for thick ones (Type III).
[src:coating/anodising] Anodized aluminium surfaces that are not regularly cleaned are susceptible to panel edge staining, a unique type of surface staining that can affect the structural integrity of the metal.
[src:coating/anodising] Anodizing is one of the more environmentally friendly metal finishing processes.
[src:coating/anodising] Except for organic (aka integral color) anodizing, the by-products contain only small amounts of heavy metals, halogens, or volatile organic compounds.
[src:coating/anodising] Integral color anodizing produces no VOCs, heavy metals, or halogens as all of the byproducts found in the effluent streams of other processes come from their dyes or plating materials.
[src:coating/anodising] The most common anodizing effluents, aluminium hydroxide and aluminium sulfate, are recycled for the manufacturing of alum, baking powder, cosmetics, newsprint and fertilizer or used by industrial wastewater treatment systems.
[src:coating/anodising] Anodizing will raise the surface since the oxide created occupies more space than the base metal converted.
[src:coating/anodising] This will generally not be of consequence except where there are tight tolerances.
[src:coating/anodising] If so, the thickness of the anodizing layer has to be taken into account when choosing the machining dimension.
[src:coating/anodising] A general practice on engineering drawing is to specify that "dimensions apply after all surface finishes".
[src:coating/anodising] This will force the machine shop to take into account the anodization thickness when performing the final machining of the mechanical part before anodization.
[src:coating/anodising] Also, in the case of small holes threaded to accept screws, anodizing may cause the screws to bind, thus, the threaded holes may need to be chased with a tap to restore the original dimensions.
[src:coating/anodising] Alternatively, special oversize taps may be used to precompensate for this growth.
[src:coating/anodising] In the case of unthreaded holes that accept fixed-diameter pins or rods, a slightly oversized hole to allow for the dimension change may be appropriate.
[src:coating/anodising] Depending on the alloy and thickness of the anodized coating, the same may have a significantly negative effect on fatigue life.
[src:coating/anodising] Conversely, anodizing may increase fatigue life by preventing corrosion pitting.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] Anti-fouling is the ability of specifically designed materials (such as toxic biocide paints, or non-toxic paints) to remove or prevent biofouling.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] The buildup of biofouling on marine vessels poses a significant problem.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] In some instances, the hull structure and propulsion systems can be damaged.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] The accumulation of biofoulers on hulls can increase both the hydrodynamic volume of a vessel and the hydrodynamic friction, leading to increased drag of up to 60%.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] The drag increase has been seen to decrease speeds by up to 10%, which can require up to a 40% increase in fuel to compensate.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] With fuel typically comprising up to half of marine transport costs, antifouling methods save the shipping industry a considerable amount of money.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] Further, increased fuel use due to biofouling contributes to adverse environmental effects and is predicted to increase emissions of carbon dioxide and sulfur dioxide between 38% and 72% by 2020, respectively.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] Biofouling organisms are highly diverse, and extend far beyond the attachment of barnacles and seaweeds.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] According to some estimates, over 1,700 species comprising over 4,000 organisms are responsible for biofouling.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] Biofouling is divided into **microfouling**—biofilm formation and bacterial adhesion—and **macrofouling**—attachment of larger organisms.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] Due to the distinct chemistry and biology that determine what prevents them from settling, organisms are also classified as hard- or soft-fouling types.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] Calcareous (hard) fouling organisms include barnacles, encrusting bryozoans, mollusks such as zebra mussels, and polychaete and other tube worms.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] Examples of non-calcareous (soft) fouling organisms are seaweed, hydroids, algae, and biofilm "slime".
[src:coating/anti-fouling] Together, these organisms form a fouling community.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] Marine fouling is typically described as following four stages of ecosystem development.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] Within the first minute the van der Waals interaction causes the submerged surface to be covered with a conditioning film of organic polymers.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] In the next 24 hours, this layer allows the process of bacterial adhesion to occur, with both diatoms and bacteria (e.g.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] *Vibrio alginolyticus*, *Pseudomonas putrefaciens*) attaching, initiating the formation of a biofilm.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] By the end of the first week, the rich nutrients and ease of attachment into the biofilm allow secondary colonizers of spores of macroalgae (e.g.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] *Enteromorpha intestinalis*, *Ulothrix*) and sessile protozoans (e.g.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] *Vorticella*, *Zoothamnium* sp.) to attach themselves.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] Within two to three weeks, the tertiary colonizers—the macrofoulers—have attached.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] These include tunicates, mollusks, and sessile cnidarians.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] Governments and industry spend more than US$5.7 billion annually to prevent and control marine biofouling.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] Biofouling occurs everywhere but is most significant economically to the shipping industries, since fouling on a ship's hull significantly increases drag, reducing the overall hydrodynamic performance of the vessel, and increases the fuel consumption.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] Biofouling is also found in almost all circumstances where water-based liquids are in contact with other materials.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] Industrially important impacts are on the maintenance of mariculture, membrane systems (*e.g.*, membrane bioreactors and reverse osmosis spiral wound membranes) and cooling water cycles of large industrial equipment and power stations.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] Biofouling can occur in oil pipelines carrying oils with entrained water, especially those carrying used oils, cutting oils, oils rendered water-soluble through emulsification, and hydraulic oils.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] Other mechanisms impacted by biofouling include microelectrochemical drug delivery devices, papermaking and pulp industry machines, underwater instruments, fire protection system piping, and sprinkler system nozzles.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] In groundwater wells, biofouling buildup can limit recovery flow rates, as is the case in the exterior and interior of ocean-laying pipes where fouling is often removed with a tube cleaning process.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] Besides interfering with mechanisms, biofouling also occurs on the surfaces of living marine organisms, when it is known as epibiosis.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] Medical devices often include fan-cooled heat sinks, to cool their electronic components.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] While these systems sometimes include HEPA filters to collect microbes, some pathogens do pass through these filters, collect inside the device and are eventually blown out and infect other patients.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] Devices used in operating rooms rarely include fans, so as to minimize the chance of transmission.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] Also, medical equipment, HVAC units, high-end computers, swimming pools, drinking-water systems and other products that utilize liquid lines run the risk of biofouling as biological growth occurs inside them.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] Historically, the focus of attention has been the severe impact due to biofouling on the speed of marine vessels.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] In some instances the hull structure and propulsion systems can become damaged.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] Over time, the accumulation of biofoulers on hulls increases both the hydrodynamic volume of a vessel and the frictional effects leading to increased drag of up to 60% The additional drag can decrease speeds up to 10%, which can require up to a 40% increase in fuel to compensate.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] With fuel typically comprising up to half of marine transport costs, biofouling is estimated to cost the US Navy alone around $1 billion per year in increased fuel usage, maintenance and biofouling control measures.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] Increased fuel use due to biofouling contributes to adverse environmental effects and is predicted to increase emissions of carbon dioxide and sulfur dioxide between 38 and 72 percent by 2020.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] Biofouling also impacts aquaculture, increasing production and management costs, while decreasing product value.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] Fouling communities may compete with shellfish directly for food resources, impede the procurement of food and oxygen by reducing water flow around shellfish, or interfere with the operational opening of their valves.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] Consequently, stock affected by biofouling can experience reduced growth, condition and survival, with subsequent negative impacts on farm productivity.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] Although many methods of removal exist, they often impact the cultured species, sometimes more so than the fouling organisms themselves.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] Shipping companies have historically relied on scheduled biofouler removal to keep such accretions to a manageable level.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] However, the rate of accretion can vary widely between vessels and operating conditions, so predicting acceptable intervals between cleanings is difficult.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] LED manufacturers have developed a range of UVC (250–280 nm) equipment that can detect biofouling buildup, and can even prevent it.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] Fouling detection relies on the biomass' property of fluorescence.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] All microorganisms contain natural intracellular fluorophores, which radiate in the UV range when excited.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] At UV-range wavelengths, such fluorescence arises from three aromatic amino acids—tyrosine, phenylalanine, and tryptophan.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] The easiest to detect is tryptophan, which radiates at 350 nm when irradiated at 280 nm.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] In 2023, the International Maritime Organization (IMO) adopted 'Guidelines for the control and management of ships' biofouling to minimize the transfer of invasive aquatic species'.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] In April 2025, the IMO agreed to develop a legally binding framework for controlling and managing ships’ biofouling to reduce the accumulation of marine organisms on the hulls of ships and thereby reduce the transfer of invasive aquatic species.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] Controlling ship's biofouling also improves the environmental efficiency of ships by reducing drag resistance.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] Non-toxic anti-sticking coatings prevent attachment of microorganisms thus negating the use of biocides.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] These coatings are usually based on organic polymers.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] There are two classes of non-toxic anti-fouling coatings.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] The most common class relies on low friction and low surface energies.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] Low surface energies result in hydrophobic surfaces.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] These coatings create a smooth surface, which can prevent attachment of larger microorganisms.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] For example, fluoropolymers and silicone coatings are commonly used.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] These coatings are ecologically inert but have problems with mechanical strength and long-term stability.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] Specifically, after days biofilms (slime) can coat the surfaces, which buries the chemical activity and allows microorganisms to attach.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] The current standard for these coatings is polydimethylsiloxane, or PDMS, which consists of a non-polar backbone made of repeating units of silicon and oxygen atoms.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] The non-polarity of PDMS allows for biomolecules to readily adsorb to its surface in order to lower interfacial energy.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] However, PDMS also has a low modulus of elasticity that allows for the release of fouling organisms at speeds of greater than 20 knots.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] The dependence of effectiveness on vessel speed prevents use of PDMS on slow-moving ships or those that spend significant amounts of time in port.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] The second class of non-toxic antifouling coatings are hydrophilic coatings.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] They rely on high amounts of hydration in order to increase the energetic penalty of removing water for proteins and microorganisms to attach.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] The most common examples of these coatings are based on highly hydrated zwitterions, such as glycine betaine and sulfobetaine.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] These coatings are also low-friction, but are considered by some to be superior to hydrophobic surfaces because they prevent bacteria attachment, preventing biofilm formation.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] These coatings are not yet commercially available and are being designed as part of a larger effort by the Office of Naval Research to develop environmentally safe biomimetic ship coatings.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] Biocides are chemical substances that kill or deter microorganisms responsible for biofouling.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] The biocide is typically applied as a paint, i.e. through physical adsorption.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] The biocides prevent the formation of biofilms.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] Other biocides are toxic to larger organisms in biofouling, such as algae.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] Formerly, the so-called tributyltin (TBT) compounds were used as biocides (and thus anti-fouling agents).
[src:coating/anti-fouling] TBTs are toxic to both microorganisms and larger aquatic organisms.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] The international maritime community has phased out the use of organotin-based coatings.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] Replacing organotin compounds is dichlorooctylisothiazolinone.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] This compound, however, also suffers from broad toxicity to marine organisms.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] Ultrasonic transducers may be mounted in or around the hull of small to medium-sized boats.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] Research has shown these systems can help reduce fouling, by initiating bursts of ultrasonic waves through the hull medium to the surrounding water, killing or denaturing the algae and other microorganisms that form the beginning of the fouling sequence.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] The systems cannot work on wooden-hulled boats, or boats with a soft-cored composite material, such as wood or foam.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] The systems have been loosely based on technology proven to control algae blooms.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] Pulsed laser irradiation is commonly used against diatoms.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] Plasma pulse technology is effective against zebra mussels and works by stunning or killing the organisms with microsecond-duration energizing of the water with high-voltage electricity.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] Similarly, another method shown to be effective against algae buildups bounces brief high-energy acoustic pulses down pipes.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] Regimens to periodically use heat to treat exchanger equipment and pipes have been successfully used to remove mussels from power plant cooling systems using water at 105 °F (40 °C) for 30 minutes.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] The medical industry utilizes a variety of energy methods to address bioburden issues associated with biofouling.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] Autoclaving typically involves heating a medical device to 121 °C (249 °F) for 15–20 minutes.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] Ultrasonic cleaning, UV light, and chemical wipe-down or immersion can also be used for different types of devices.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] UVC irradiation is a noncontact, nonchemical solution that can be used across a range of instruments.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] Radiation in the UVC range prevents biofilm formation by deactivating the DNA in bacteria, viruses, and other microbes.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] Preventing biofilm formation prevents larger organisms from attaching themselves to the instrument and eventually rendering it inoperable.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] Biofouling, especially of ships, has been a problem for as long as humans have been sailing the oceans.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] The earliest attestations of attempts to counter fouling, and thus also the earliest attestation of knowledge of it, is the use of pitch and copper plating as anti-fouling solutions that were attributed to ancient seafaring nations, such as the Phoenicians and Carthaginians (1500–300 BC).
[src:coating/anti-fouling] Wax, tar and asphaltum have been used since early times.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] An Aramaic record dating from 412 BC tells of a ship's bottom being coated with a mixture of arsenic, oil and sulphur.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] In *Deipnosophistae*, Athenaeus described the anti-fouling efforts taken in the construction of the great ship of Hieron of Syracuse (died 467 BC).
[src:coating/anti-fouling] Before the 18th century, various anti-fouling techniques were used, with three main substances employed: "White stuff", a mixture of train oil (whale oil), rosin and sulfur; "Black stuff", a mixture of tar and pitch; and "Brown stuff", which was simply sulfur added to Black stuff.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] In many of these cases, the purpose of these treatments is ambiguous.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] There is dispute whether many of these treatments were actual anti-fouling techniques, or whether, when they were used in conjunction with lead and wood sheathing, they were simply intended to combat wood-boring shipworms.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] In 1708, Charles Perry suggested copper sheathing explicitly as an anti-fouling device but the first experiments were not made until 1761 with the sheathing of HMS Alarm, after which the bottoms and sides of several ships' keels and false keels were sheathed with copper plates.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] The copper performed well in protecting the hull from invasion by worm, and in preventing the growth of weed, for when in contact with water, the copper produced a poisonous film, composed mainly of oxychloride, that deterred these marine creatures.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] Furthermore, as this film was slightly soluble, it gradually washed away, leaving no way for marine life to attach itself to the ship.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] From about 1770, the Royal Navy set about coppering the bottoms of the entire fleet and continued to the end of the use of wooden ships.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] The process was so successful that the term *copper-bottomed* came to mean something that was highly dependable or risk free.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] With the rise of iron hulls in the 19th century, copper sheathing could no longer be used due to its galvanic corrosive interaction with iron.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] Anti-fouling paints were tried, and in 1860, the first practical paint to gain widespread use was introduced in Liverpool and was referred to as "McIness" hot plastic paint.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] These treatments had a short service life, were expensive, and relatively ineffective by modern standards.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] By the mid-twentieth century, copper oxide-based paints could keep a ship out of drydock for as much as 18 months, or as little as 12 in tropical waters.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] The shorter service life was due to rapid leaching of the toxicant, and chemical conversion into less toxic salts, which accumulated as a crust that would inhibit further leaching of active cuprous oxide from the layer under the crust.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] The 1960s brought a breakthrough, with self-polishing paints that slowly hydrolyze, slowly releasing toxins.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] These paints employed organotin chemistry ("tin-based") biotoxins such as tributyltin oxide (TBT) and were effective for up to four years.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] These biotoxins were subsequently banned by the International Maritime Organization when they were found to be very toxic to diverse organisms.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] TBT in particular has been described as the most toxic pollutant ever deliberately released in the ocean.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] As an alternative to organotin toxins, there has been renewed interest in copper as the active agent in ablative or self polishing paints, with reported service lives up to 5 years; yet also other methods that do not involve coatings.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] Modern adhesives permit application of copper alloys to steel hulls without creating galvanic corrosion.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] However, copper alone is not impervious to diatom and algae fouling.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] Some studies indicate that copper may also present an unacceptable environmental impact.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] Study of biofouling began in the early 19th century with Davy's experiments linking the effectiveness of copper to its solute rate.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] In the 1930s microbiologist Claude ZoBell showed that the attachment of organisms is preceded by the adsorption of organic compounds now referred to as extracellular polymeric substances.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] One trend of research is the study of the relationship between wettability and anti-fouling effectiveness.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] Another trend is the study of living organisms as the inspiration for new functional materials.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] For example, the mechanisms used by marine animals to inhibit biofouling on their skin.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] A study of the biotoxins used by organisms has revealed several effective compounds, some of which are more powerful than synthetic compounds.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] Bufalin, a bufotoxin, was found to be over 100 times as potent as TBT, and over 6,000 times more effective in anti-settlement activity against barnacles.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] One approach to antifouling entails coating surfaces with polyethylene glycol (PEG).
[src:coating/anti-fouling] Growing chains of PEG on surfaces is challenging.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] The resolution to this problem may come from understanding the mechanisms by which mussels adhere to solid surfaces in marine environments.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] Mussels utilize adhesive proteins, or MAPs.
[src:coating/anti-fouling] The service life of PEG coatings is also doubtful.
[src:coating/coating] A **coating** is a covering that is applied to the surface of an object, or substrate.
[src:coating/coating] The purpose of applying the coating may be decorative, functional, or both.
[src:coating/coating] Coatings may be applied as liquids, gases or solids e.g. powder coatings.
[src:coating/coating] Along with corrosion resistance, functional coatings may also be applied to change the surface properties of the substrate, such as adhesion, wettability, or wear resistance.
[src:coating/coating] In other cases the coating adds a completely new property, such as a magnetic response or electrical conductivity (as in semiconductor device fabrication, where the substrate is a wafer), and forms an essential part of the finished product.
[src:coating/coating] A major consideration for most coating processes is controlling coating thickness.
[src:coating/coating] Methods of achieving this range from a simple brush to expensive precision machinery in the electronics industry.
[src:coating/coating] Limiting coating area is crucial in some applications, such as printing.
[src:coating/coating] "Roll-to-roll" or "web-based" coating is the process of applying a thin film of functional material to a substrate on a roll, such as paper, fabric, film, foil, or sheet stock.
[src:coating/coating] This continuous process is highly efficient for producing large volumes of coated materials, which are essential in various industries including printing, packaging, and electronics.
[src:coating/coating] The technology allows for consistent high-quality application of the coating material over large surface areas, enhancing productivity and uniformity.
[src:coating/coating] Coatings can be both decorative and have other functions.
[src:coating/coating] A pipe carrying water for a fire suppression system can be coated with a red (for identification) anticorrosion paint.
[src:coating/coating] Most coatings to some extent protect the substrate, such as maintenance coatings for metals and concrete.
[src:coating/coating] A decorative coating can offer a particular reflective property, such as high gloss, satin, matte, or flat appearance.
[src:coating/coating] A major coating application is to protect metal from corrosion.
[src:coating/coating] Automotive coatings are used to enhance the appearance and durability of vehicles.
[src:coating/coating] These include primers, basecoats, and clearcoats, primarily applied with spray guns and electrostatically.
[src:coating/coating] The body and underbody of automobiles receive some form of underbody coating.
[src:coating/coating] Such anticorrosion coatings may use graphene in combination with water-based epoxies.
[src:coating/coating] Coatings are used to seal the surface of concrete, such as seamless polymer/resin flooring, bund wall/containment lining, waterproofing and damp proofing concrete walls, and bridge decks.
[src:coating/coating] Compare with tradition coatings, moisture curing polyurethane has been widely used because of the excellent adaptability and ease of construction.
[src:coating/coating] The mechanical properties could be enhanced by introducing multiple hydrogen bonds and optimize the microphase separation structure.
[src:coating/coating] Most roof coatings are designed primarily for waterproofing, though sun reflection (to reduce heating and cooling) may also be a consideration.
[src:coating/coating] They tend to be elastomeric to allow for movement of the roof without cracking within the coating membrane.
[src:coating/coating] Wood has been a key material in construction since ancient times, so its preservation by coating has received much attention.
[src:coating/coating] Efforts to improve the performance of wood coatings continue.
[src:coating/coating] Coatings are used to alter tribological properties and wear characteristics.
[src:coating/coating] Architectural coatings or paints are used to paint the exteriors and interiors of buildings, often called or external masonry coatings.
[src:coating/coating] Clear varnishes and lacquers are generally excluded.
[src:coating/coating] Such products are usually designated for specific purposes such as roof coatings, wall paints, or deck finishes.
[src:coating/coating] Coatings are eco-friendly building material that increases the efficiency of energy used and reduces impact on human well-being and the environment.
[src:coating/coating] The coatings are typically applied with brushes, rollers or sprayers.
[src:coating/coating] Wall coatings come in a variety of types, some of which can be applied by amateurs and DIYers without specialized training or equipment.
[src:coating/coating] For example, simple paint or primers can often be applied using brushes or rollers, and many people successfully complete such projects themselves.
[src:coating/coating] Most masonry surfaces can be treated an exterior wall coating, such as render, pebbledash, stone, stucco or brick.
[src:coating/coating] These coatings are intended for on-site application and do not include "factory-applied coatings for building products such as vinyl siding or aluminium window frames [that] may ultimately be used for architectural end-uses".
[src:coating/coating] Numerous destructive and non-destructive evaluation (NDE) methods exist for characterizing coatings.
[src:coating/coating] The most common destructive method is microscopy of a mounted cross-section of the coating and its substrate.
[src:coating/coating] The most common non-destructive techniques include ultrasonic thickness measurement, X-ray fluorescence (XRF), X-Ray diffraction (XRD), photothermal coating thickness measurement and micro hardness indentation.
[src:coating/coating] X-ray photoelectron spectroscopy (XPS) is also a classical characterization method to investigate the chemical composition of the nanometer thick surface layer of a material.
[src:coating/coating] Scanning electron microscopy coupled with energy dispersive X-ray spectrometry (SEM-EDX, or SEM-EDS) allows to visualize the surface texture and to probe its elementary chemical composition.
[src:coating/coating] Other characterization methods include transmission electron microscopy (TEM), atomic force microscopy (AFM), scanning tunneling microscope (STM), and Rutherford backscattering spectrometry (RBS).
[src:coating/coating] Various methods of Chromatography are also used, as well as thermogravimetric analysis.
[src:coating/coating] The formulation of a coating depends primarily on the function required of the coating and also on aesthetics required such as color and gloss.
[src:coating/coating] The four primary ingredients are the resin (or binder), solvent which may be water (or solventless), pigment(s) and additives (defoamers, surfactants, optical brighteners, etc.).
[src:coating/coating] Research is ongoing to remove heavy metals from coating formulations completely.
[src:coating/coating] For example, on the basis of experimental and epidemiological evidence, it has been classified by the IARC (International Agency for Research on Cancer) as a human carcinogen by inhalation (class I) (ISPESL, 2008).
